-- FINANCE 1: Cash Management Best Practices for Startups
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('finance', 'best-practices', 'Cash Management Best Practices for Startups',
 'Core cash management principles including reserve targets, AR aging, payment terms, and weekly review cadence.',
 E'## Cash Management Best Practices for Startups\n\nCash is the lifeblood of any early-stage company. For Ascent XR, where revenue is lumpy and tied to school district purchasing cycles, disciplined cash management is non-negotiable.\n\n### The 3-Month Operating Reserve Rule\n\nMaintain a minimum of three months of operating expenses in a high-yield savings or money-market account at all times. If monthly burn is $25,000, the reserve target is $75,000. This buffer protects against delayed school district payments (which routinely take 45-90 days) and seasonal revenue dips during summer months when districts are between fiscal years.\n\n### Accounts Receivable Aging Buckets\n\nTrack every outstanding invoice in four buckets:\n\n| Bucket | Age | Action |\n|--------|-----|--------|\n| Current | 0-30 days | Monitor; no action needed |\n| Watch | 31-60 days | Send friendly reminder at day 35; call AP contact at day 45 |\n| At Risk | 61-90 days | Escalate to district business manager; consider offering payment plan |\n| Critical | 90+ days | Formal demand letter; engage collections or legal review |\n\nFor school districts, the 31-60 day bucket is common and not cause for alarm. Many districts batch payments on a 45-day cycle. The key is to prevent invoices from reaching 90+ days, where recovery rates drop below 70%.\n\n### Payment Terms Strategy\n\n- **Standard terms**: Net 30 for most school districts\n- **Large districts (10,000+ students)**: Net 45 acceptable given volume\n- **Custom XR projects over $25,000**: 50% deposit upon signed SOW, 25% at milestone review, 25% upon delivery\n- **Subscription licenses**: Annual prepay with 10% discount, or quarterly billing at list price\n- **Pilot programs**: 100% prepay required (small dollar amounts, $2,000)\n\n### Weekly Cash Position Review\n\nEvery Monday morning, review:\n\n1. **Current bank balances** across all accounts\n2. **Expected inflows** for the next 14 days (confirmed POs and scheduled payments)\n3. **Committed outflows** for the next 14 days (payroll, rent, subscriptions, contractor invoices)\n4. **Net cash position** = Current balance + Expected inflows - Committed outflows\n5. **Variance from forecast** - flag anything more than 10% off the 13-week plan\n\n### Separate Bank Accounts\n\nMaintain at least three accounts:\n\n- **Operating Account**: Day-to-day expenses, payroll, vendor payments\n- **Tax Reserve Account**: Set aside 30% of every revenue dollar received for federal, state, and self-employment taxes\n- **Reserve Account**: The 3-month buffer; do not touch for operations\n\n### Key Metrics to Track Weekly\n\n- **Days Cash on Hand**: Current cash / (Monthly operating expenses / 30). Target: 90+ days\n- **Quick Ratio**: (Cash + AR) / Current liabilities. Target: 1.5 or higher\n- **Cash Conversion Cycle**: Days Sales Outstanding + Days Inventory Outstanding - Days Payable Outstanding. For a services/SaaS company, focus on DSO (target under 45 days)\n- **Burn Rate**: Total cash out per month, excluding one-time capital expenditures\n- **Cash Runway**: Current cash / Monthly net burn. Target: 12+ months',
 ARRAY['cash-management', 'reserves', 'AR-aging', 'payment-terms', 'weekly-review', 'startup-finance'],
 true, 10);

-- FINANCE 2: Revenue Recognition for EdTech SaaS
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('finance', 'accounting', 'Revenue Recognition for EdTech SaaS',
 'ASC 606 five-step revenue recognition model applied to Ascent XR subscription, custom project, and pilot revenue streams.',
 E'## Revenue Recognition for EdTech SaaS\n\nProper revenue recognition under ASC 606 is critical even for early-stage companies. Getting it right from day one avoids painful restatements later and builds investor confidence.\n\n### ASC 606 Five-Step Model\n\n1. **Identify the contract** - Signed SOW, PO, or subscription agreement with a school district\n2. **Identify performance obligations** - Each distinct deliverable (platform access, custom content, training sessions, support)\n3. **Determine the transaction price** - Total contract value including any variable consideration (usage tiers, success bonuses)\n4. **Allocate the price** to each performance obligation based on standalone selling price\n5. **Recognize revenue** as each obligation is satisfied (over time or at a point in time)\n\n### Subscription Revenue (District Licenses)\n\nDistrict subscription licenses ($3,000-$10,000/year) are recognized **ratably over the subscription term**. A $6,000 annual license starting October 1 generates $500/month in recognized revenue. Even if the district pays the full $6,000 upfront, the remaining balance sits in Deferred Revenue on the balance sheet.\n\n- **Monthly recognition**: Contract value / Term in months\n- **Example**: $8,000 annual license, July 1 start = $666.67/month recognized\n- **Multi-year deals**: Each year''s portion is recognized in that year; future years remain in long-term deferred revenue\n\n### Custom XR Projects\n\nCustom immersive experiences ($15,000-$50,000) use the **percentage-of-completion method** when the project spans more than one reporting period:\n\n- Track costs incurred vs. total estimated costs\n- Revenue recognized = (Costs incurred to date / Total estimated costs) x Total contract value\n- **Example**: $30,000 project, $12,000 of estimated $20,000 in costs incurred = 60% complete = $18,000 recognized\n- Update estimates monthly; if total cost estimate changes, adjust cumulative recognition in current period\n\nAlternatively, for shorter projects (under 3 months), **milestone-based recognition** is acceptable:\n- 25% at design approval\n- 50% at beta delivery\n- 25% at final acceptance\n\n### Professional Services\n\nConsulting, training, and implementation services at $150/hour are recognized **as delivered**. Track hours weekly and recognize revenue in the period the service is performed. For fixed-fee service packages, use the same percentage-of-completion approach as custom projects.\n\n### Pilot Programs\n\nPilot revenue ($2,000 per 90-day pilot) is **deferred until conversion criteria are met** or the pilot period ends. If the pilot converts to a full subscription, the $2,000 is recognized upon signing the full contract. If the pilot expires without conversion, recognize the $2,000 at expiration since the service was fully delivered.\n\n### Practical Pricing Tier Examples\n\n| Product | Price Range | Recognition Method | Timing |\n|---------|-------------|-------------------|--------|\n| District Subscription | $3,000-$10,000/yr | Ratably over term | Monthly |\n| Custom XR Experience | $15,000-$50,000 | % completion or milestone | As earned |\n| Professional Services | $150/hr or fixed fee | As delivered | Monthly |\n| Pilot Program | $2,000 flat | Deferred | At conversion or expiry |',
 ARRAY['revenue-recognition', 'ASC-606', 'SaaS', 'subscription', 'deferred-revenue', 'edtech'],
 false, 8);

-- FINANCE 3: Financial Controls for Small Companies
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('finance', 'compliance', 'Financial Controls for Small Companies',
 'Essential internal controls including segregation of duties, approval thresholds, reconciliation processes, and audit trail requirements.',
 E'## Financial Controls for Small Companies\n\nEven with a small team, basic financial controls prevent fraud, catch errors early, and satisfy auditors and investors. The goal is not bureaucracy but accountability.\n\n### Segregation of Duties (Even With 2 People)\n\nThe principle: no single person should control an entire financial transaction from initiation to completion. With a small team, achieve this through:\n\n- **Person A** initiates expenses and writes checks; **Person B** reviews and approves\n- **Person A** handles invoicing; **Person B** reconciles bank statements\n- Use software-enforced approval workflows where possible (QuickBooks approval routing, Expensify policy rules)\n- **Compensating control**: If true segregation is impossible, the owner reviews 100% of bank and credit card statements monthly with supporting documentation\n\n### Approval Workflows by Amount\n\n| Amount | Approver | Documentation Required |\n|--------|----------|----------------------|\n| Under $500 | Any team member (self-approve) | Receipt or invoice |\n| $500 - $2,500 | Manager/co-founder approval | Receipt + business justification |\n| $2,500 - $10,000 | Owner/CEO approval | Receipt + justification + competitive quote |\n| Over $10,000 | Owner/CEO + board notification | Full vendor evaluation + signed agreement |\n\n### Monthly Bank Reconciliation\n\nComplete within 10 business days of month-end:\n\n1. Match every bank transaction to a corresponding entry in QuickBooks\n2. Investigate and resolve all discrepancies over $10\n3. Verify no unauthorized transactions\n4. Reconcile credit card statements to receipts\n5. Document reconciliation with preparer and reviewer sign-off\n6. File reconciliation report in shared drive for audit trail\n\n### Expense Receipt Requirements\n\nPer IRS regulations, receipts are **required for any expense of $75 or more**. Best practice: capture receipts for everything over $25. For each expense, document:\n\n- Date of purchase\n- Vendor name\n- Amount\n- Business purpose (brief description)\n- Project or client allocation (if applicable)\n\nUse Expensify or similar tool for real-time receipt capture via mobile photo. Set a policy: receipts must be uploaded within 48 hours of purchase.\n\n### Quarterly Variance Analysis\n\nEvery quarter, compare actual results to budget:\n\n- Flag any line item with variance greater than 15% or $1,000 (whichever is less)\n- Prepare a written explanation for each flagged variance\n- Identify trends: are we consistently over-budget in a category?\n- Adjust the forward budget based on run-rate actuals\n- Present findings in a 1-page summary to stakeholders\n\n### Audit Trail Requirements\n\nMaintain a clear, unbroken paper trail for every financial transaction:\n\n- **Invoices**: Saved as PDF with unique numbering, linked to PO and contract\n- **Payments received**: Bank deposit matched to invoice, noted in accounting system\n- **Expenses**: Receipt + approval email/workflow + accounting entry\n- **Journal entries**: Description of what, why, and who approved\n- **Payroll**: Pay stubs, tax withholding calculations, benefit deductions\n\n### Recommended Tools\n\n- **Accounting**: QuickBooks Online (Plus or Advanced plan) - $80-$200/month\n- **Expense Management**: Expensify - $5/user/month\n- **Banking**: Mercury or Relay for startup-friendly features and API integrations\n- **Payroll**: Gusto - $40/month + $6/person\n- **Document Storage**: Google Drive with structured folder hierarchy and access controls',
 ARRAY['internal-controls', 'segregation-of-duties', 'approval-workflows', 'reconciliation', 'audit-trail', 'compliance'],
 false, 7);

-- FINANCE 4: Startup Metrics That Matter
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('finance', 'metrics', 'Startup Metrics That Matter',
 'Key SaaS and startup financial metrics including MRR/ARR, burn rate, CAC, LTV, churn, and education-specific seasonality adjustments.',
 E'## Startup Metrics That Matter\n\nInvestors, advisors, and your own decision-making depend on tracking the right metrics. For an EdTech SaaS company selling to school districts, standard SaaS metrics need education-specific adjustments.\n\n### MRR / ARR (Monthly & Annual Recurring Revenue)\n\n- **MRR** = Sum of all active monthly subscription values. A $6,000 annual license = $500 MRR.\n- **ARR** = MRR x 12. This is the headline metric investors care about most.\n- Track **New MRR** (new customers), **Expansion MRR** (upgrades), **Churned MRR** (cancellations), and **Net New MRR** separately.\n- **Important**: Do not include one-time revenue (custom projects, pilots) in MRR/ARR. Track those as non-recurring revenue.\n\n### Burn Rate\n\n- **Gross Burn**: Total cash spent per month, all categories. If you spend $30,000/month total, gross burn = $30,000.\n- **Net Burn**: Total cash out minus total cash in. If you spend $30,000 and bring in $8,000, net burn = $22,000.\n- Track both monthly and report the 3-month rolling average to smooth out lumpy education revenue.\n\n### Runway Calculation\n\nRunway = Total cash on hand / Monthly net burn rate.\n\n- Example: $180,000 in the bank / $22,000 net burn = 8.2 months of runway\n- **Target**: Always maintain 12+ months of runway. Begin fundraising or revenue acceleration when runway drops below 9 months.\n- Recalculate runway weekly using the 13-week cash flow forecast.\n\n### Customer Acquisition Cost (CAC)\n\nCAC = Total sales and marketing spend / Number of new customers acquired (in a given period).\n\n- **Direct sales CAC**: Salary + travel + demo costs allocated per closed deal. Typically $3,000-$8,000 per district.\n- **Marketing CAC**: Ad spend + content creation + conference costs / marketing-sourced closed deals. Target under $5,000.\n- **Blended CAC**: Total S&M spend / total new customers. Track monthly and quarterly.\n- For education: measure over 6-month periods due to long sales cycles (3-9 months from lead to close).\n\n### Lifetime Value (LTV)\n\nLTV = Average revenue per account per year x Gross margin % x Average customer lifespan in years.\n\n- Education customers are sticky: average SaaS retention in K-12 is 85-90% annually once past year one.\n- Example: $7,000 ARPA x 80% margin x 5-year average lifespan = $28,000 LTV\n- Conservative estimate uses 3-year lifespan until you have actual retention data.\n\n### LTV:CAC Ratio\n\n- **Target**: 3:1 or higher (every $1 spent acquiring a customer returns $3+ in lifetime value)\n- **Below 1:1**: Unsustainable; you are paying more to acquire customers than they are worth\n- **1:1 to 3:1**: Investable but needs improvement in retention, pricing, or acquisition efficiency\n- **Above 5:1**: May indicate under-investment in growth; consider increasing sales/marketing spend\n\n### Rule of 40\n\nRevenue growth rate (%) + Profit margin (%) should exceed 40%. For early-stage startups, high growth compensates for negative margins. Example: 80% YoY growth + (-30%) margin = 50% (healthy).\n\n### Churn Rate Types\n\n- **Logo churn**: Percentage of customers lost. If you start the quarter with 20 districts and lose 2, logo churn = 10% quarterly.\n- **Revenue churn (gross)**: MRR lost from cancellations / Starting MRR. Target under 5% annually for education SaaS.\n- **Net revenue churn**: (Churned MRR - Expansion MRR) / Starting MRR. Negative net churn means expansion revenue exceeds losses -- the holy grail.\n\n### Education-Specific Seasonality\n\n- **July-September**: Peak purchasing (new fiscal year budgets). Expect 40-50% of annual new deals.\n- **October-December**: Implementation and onboarding. Low new sales activity.\n- **January-March**: Budget planning begins; districts identify needs for next year. Pipeline building season.\n- **April-June**: Budget approvals and year-end spend. Secondary purchasing window for remaining funds.\n- **Summer (June-August)**: Decision-maker availability drops. Focus on proposals and demos, not cold outreach.',
 ARRAY['MRR', 'ARR', 'burn-rate', 'runway', 'CAC', 'LTV', 'churn', 'rule-of-40', 'SaaS-metrics', 'education-seasonality'],
 true, 9);

-- FINANCE 5: 13-Week Cash Flow Forecast Template
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('finance', 'templates', '13-Week Cash Flow Forecast Template',
 'Week-by-week cash flow forecasting framework with categories, education-specific timing, and scenario modeling guidance.',
 E'## 13-Week Cash Flow Forecast Template\n\nThe 13-week cash flow forecast is the single most important financial tool for a startup. It provides a rolling 3-month view of cash inflows and outflows, updated weekly, giving you early warning of potential shortfalls.\n\n### Framework Structure\n\nEach week occupies one column. Rows are grouped into four major categories:\n\n**Section 1: Operating Receipts**\n- Subscription payments received\n- Custom project milestone payments\n- Professional services invoices collected\n- Pilot program payments\n- Grant or award disbursements\n- Other income (interest, refunds)\n\n**Section 2: Operating Disbursements**\n- Payroll and payroll taxes (semi-monthly or bi-weekly)\n- Contractor payments (Net 15)\n- Software subscriptions (monthly, typically 1st or 15th)\n- Rent and utilities\n- Insurance premiums\n- Marketing and advertising spend\n- Travel and entertainment\n- Office supplies and equipment\n- Legal and professional fees\n- Miscellaneous operating expenses\n\n**Section 3: Debt Service**\n- Loan principal payments\n- Interest payments\n- Line of credit draws or repayments\n\n**Section 4: Capital Expenditures**\n- Hardware purchases (VR headsets, computers)\n- Software licenses (perpetual, not SaaS)\n- Furniture and office buildout\n\n**Bottom Section: Summary**\n- Beginning cash balance\n- Total receipts\n- Total disbursements\n- Net cash flow (receipts - disbursements)\n- Ending cash balance\n- Minimum cash threshold line (visual alert if balance approaches reserve)\n\n### Rolling vs. Static Approach\n\nUse a **rolling forecast**: each week, drop the completed week and add a new Week 13 to the end. This ensures you always have a 13-week forward view. Never use a static quarterly forecast that goes stale.\n\n- **Weeks 1-4**: High confidence. Based on confirmed POs, scheduled payroll, and known obligations.\n- **Weeks 5-8**: Medium confidence. Based on pipeline probability-weighted inflows and committed but adjustable expenses.\n- **Weeks 9-13**: Lower confidence. Based on forecast assumptions and trend extrapolation.\n\n### Education-Specific Inflow Timing\n\nSchool districts operate on a **July 1 - June 30 fiscal year**:\n\n- **July-August**: New fiscal year budgets are active. Expect a spike in PO issuance, but payment may lag 30-45 days. Budget your receipts for August-September.\n- **October-November**: Steady-state payments on Q1 invoices. Good cash flow period.\n- **March-April**: Slower collections as districts manage mid-year budgets.\n- **May-June**: **Q4 budget flush** -- districts rush to spend remaining budget before fiscal year end. Expect a secondary receipts spike. Offer quick-turn projects or prepaid subscriptions to capture this spend.\n\n### Scenario Modeling\n\nMaintain three scenarios updated weekly:\n\n- **Optimistic**: All pipeline deals close on schedule; no payment delays; includes stretch revenue targets. Use 120% of base receipts.\n- **Base Case**: Weighted pipeline closes at historical conversion rates; standard payment timing. This is your operating plan.\n- **Pessimistic**: 50% of uncertain pipeline slips; one major payment delayed 30+ days; one unexpected expense. Use 70% of base receipts and 110% of base disbursements.\n\n### Variance Tracking\n\nEach week, record the actual result next to the forecast for the completed week:\n\n- Calculate variance ($ and %) for both receipts and disbursements\n- Investigate any variance over 10% or $2,000\n- Adjust the remaining 12 weeks based on the new information\n- Track cumulative forecast accuracy over time (target: within 10% of actual on a 4-week rolling basis)',
 ARRAY['cash-flow', 'forecast', '13-week', 'template', 'scenario-modeling', 'education-fiscal-year'],
 false, 7);

-- FINANCE 6: Budget Planning for Education Sales Cycles
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('finance', 'planning', 'Budget Planning for Education Sales Cycles',
 'Aligning company budget and marketing spend with the K-12 school district fiscal year, purchasing timelines, and federal funding windows.',
 E'## Budget Planning for Education Sales Cycles\n\nSelling to schools means aligning your financial planning with the education calendar, not the standard business calendar. Missing the budget window means waiting an entire year for the next opportunity.\n\n### School Fiscal Year vs. Calendar Year\n\nMost school districts in Indiana and nationally operate on a **July 1 - June 30 fiscal year**. This means:\n\n- Budgets are approved in May-June for the upcoming fiscal year\n- New money becomes available July 1\n- Unspent funds typically expire June 30 (use-it-or-lose-it in many districts)\n- Your company''s calendar-year financial planning must account for this offset\n\n### Budget Decision Timeline\n\n| Period | District Activity | Ascent XR Action |\n|--------|-------------------|------------------|\n| **January - March** | Superintendent and curriculum directors identify needs and priorities for next year | Conduct needs assessments, deliver ROI presentations, respond to RFIs |\n| **April - May** | School boards review and approve budgets; line items are locked | Ensure your solution is included as a named line item or approved vendor |\n| **June** | Final budget ratification; purchasing authority delegated | Submit proposals and quotes for July execution |\n| **July - September** | New fiscal year begins; active purchasing period | Close deals, execute contracts, begin onboarding |\n| **October - December** | Implementation focus; limited new purchasing | Deliver services, build case studies, gather testimonials |\n| **January - March** | Cycle repeats; mid-year budget adjustments possible | Re-engage for renewals and expansion |\n\n### Federal Funding Deadlines\n\n**ESSER Funds (Elementary and Secondary School Emergency Relief)**:\n- ESSER III funds must be **obligated (committed via PO or contract) by September 30, 2024**\n- Funds must be **fully expended by January 28, 2025**\n- After these dates, ESSER money is no longer available. Any Ascent XR proposals targeting ESSER funds must be signed and PO''d before these deadlines.\n\n**Title IV-A (Student Support and Academic Enrichment)**:\n- Annual allocation, typically $10,000-$50,000 per district depending on size\n- Funds can be used for educational technology including XR/VR\n- Districts apply in spring; funds available in fall\n- Renewals are annual; build Ascent XR into the district''s Title IV-A plan each spring\n\n**E-Rate (Universal Service Fund)**:\n- Primarily for internet and telecom, but can cover some infrastructure supporting digital learning\n- Application window: January - March annually\n- Funding commitments issued July - September\n\n### Marketing Spend Alignment\n\nAlign your marketing budget with the buying cycle:\n\n- **Q1 (Jan-Mar)**: Heaviest marketing spend (35% of annual budget). Conference attendance (ISTE, state EdTech conferences), targeted ads, webinars for curriculum directors. This is when districts are planning.\n- **Q2 (Apr-Jun)**: Moderate spend (25%). Focus on proposal support, case study distribution, board presentation materials.\n- **Q3 (Jul-Sep)**: Moderate spend (25%). Closing support, onboarding materials, customer success stories for reference calls.\n- **Q4 (Oct-Dec)**: Lightest spend (15%). Nurture campaigns, thought leadership content, ROI tools for renewal conversations.\n\n### Budget Planning Checklist\n\n1. Map your revenue forecast to the school fiscal year, not the calendar year\n2. Build a district-by-district pipeline with expected PO dates aligned to their budget cycle\n3. Front-load marketing spend to January-March to influence next-year budgets\n4. Track federal funding deadlines and create urgency campaigns around them\n5. Plan for cash flow gaps in April-June when district purchasing pauses for budget approval\n6. Reserve contingency budget (10%) for opportunistic mid-year purchases',
 ARRAY['budget-planning', 'education-sales-cycle', 'school-fiscal-year', 'ESSER', 'Title-IV-A', 'marketing-alignment'],
 false, 6);

-- FINANCE 7: Invoice Best Practices
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('finance', 'operations', 'Invoice Best Practices',
 'Invoice formatting, numbering, payment terms for K-12, required fields for school district compliance, and follow-up cadence.',
 E'## Invoice Best Practices\n\nProfessional, compliant invoicing accelerates payment and reduces friction with school district accounts payable departments. Districts process thousands of invoices; yours needs to be easy to match and approve.\n\n### Invoice Numbering System\n\nUse a consistent, sortable format: **INV-YYYYMM-NNN**\n\n- INV-202601-001 = First invoice of January 2026\n- INV-202601-002 = Second invoice of January 2026\n- The sequential number resets to 001 each month\n- Never reuse or skip numbers; gaps trigger audit questions\n- For credit memos: **CM-YYYYMM-NNN**\n\n### Payment Terms by Customer Type\n\n| Customer Type | Standard Terms | Notes |\n|--------------|----------------|-------|\n| Small district (<2,000 students) | Net 30 | Faster AP processing; smaller bureaucracy |\n| Medium district (2,000-10,000) | Net 30-45 | Standard processing time |\n| Large district (10,000+) | Net 45-60 | Complex approval chains; budget office review |\n| State agencies | Net 60 | Mandatory state payment schedules |\n| Private schools | Net 30 | Generally faster payment |\n\nAlways confirm the district''s standard payment terms before invoicing. Some districts have fixed payment cycles (e.g., checks cut on the 1st and 15th only) regardless of your terms.\n\n### Required Fields for School District Invoicing\n\nDistrict AP departments will reject invoices missing any of these:\n\n1. **Purchase Order (PO) Number** - Reference the exact PO number on every invoice. No PO, no payment.\n2. **Budget Code / Account Code** - If provided by the district, include their internal budget code\n3. **Vendor ID** - Your assigned vendor number in their system\n4. **Detailed description of goods/services** - Not just \"Consulting\" but \"Professional development training for 15 teachers, XR content creation workshop, 6 hours on-site at Lincoln Elementary, January 15, 2026\"\n5. **Unit pricing** - Break down line items with quantity, unit price, and extended price\n6. **Tax-exempt notation** - School districts are tax-exempt; do not charge sales tax. Note \"Customer is tax-exempt\" on the invoice.\n7. **W-9 on file** - Ensure the district has your W-9 before first invoice; many won''t pay without it\n8. **Remit-to address** - Physical and/or electronic payment instructions\n\n### Follow-Up Cadence\n\n- **Day 7 (before due)**: Courtesy email -- \"Your invoice INV-202601-001 for $X,XXX is due on [date]. Please let us know if you need any documentation.\"\n- **Day 14 (at due date or just past)**: Friendly reminder -- \"Invoice INV-202601-001 was due on [date]. Is there anything holding up processing?\"\n- **Day 21**: Phone call to the AP contact. Ask if the invoice is in the payment queue and expected payment date.\n- **Day 30 (if past due)**: Email to AP contact CC''ing your district champion (curriculum director or principal). Politely escalate.\n- **Day 45+**: Contact the district business manager or CFO. For large amounts, consider offering a payment plan.\n\n### Late Payment Handling for Government Entities\n\nSchool districts are government entities. Charging late fees is generally **not recommended** as it damages relationships and districts may dispute or ignore them. Instead:\n\n- Document the delay in your records\n- Factor expected payment timing into your cash flow forecast\n- For chronic late payers, negotiate prepayment or deposit terms on future contracts\n- Indiana Prompt Payment Act (IC 5-17-5) requires government entities to pay within 35 days or pay interest at 1% per month, but enforcing this against a school district customer is a last resort\n\n### Electronic Invoicing\n\nMany districts now accept or prefer electronic invoices:\n\n- **Email PDF**: Most common; send to the dedicated AP email address, not your contact''s personal email\n- **Vendor portals**: Large districts use platforms like SAP Ariba, Coupa, or custom portals. Register and submit through their system.\n- **EDI/E-invoicing**: Less common in K-12 but growing. Be prepared to support if requested.\n- Always retain proof of submission (email confirmation, portal receipt number)',
 ARRAY['invoicing', 'payment-terms', 'K-12', 'accounts-receivable', 'follow-up', 'school-districts'],
 false, 5);

-- FINANCE 8: Break-Even Analysis for XR Education Company
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('finance', 'analysis', 'Break-Even Analysis for XR Education Company',
 'Fixed and variable cost breakdown, contribution margin by product line, break-even calculation, and sensitivity analysis for Ascent XR.',
 E'## Break-Even Analysis for XR Education Company\n\nUnderstanding your break-even point tells you exactly how much revenue is needed to cover all costs. For Ascent XR, with multiple revenue streams and different margin profiles, a blended break-even analysis is essential.\n\n### Fixed Costs (Monthly)\n\n| Category | Monthly Cost | Annual Cost | Notes |\n|----------|-------------|-------------|-------|\n| Founder salary | $6,000 | $72,000 | Below market; will increase |\n| Part-time developer | $4,000 | $48,000 | Contract, 20 hrs/week |\n| Software subscriptions | $800 | $9,600 | Unity, Adobe, AWS, CRM, etc. |\n| Insurance (general liability + E&O) | $250 | $3,000 | Required for school contracts |\n| Office/coworking space | $400 | $4,800 | Shared space or home office |\n| Accounting/legal retainer | $500 | $6,000 | Monthly bookkeeping + quarterly review |\n| Internet/phone/utilities | $200 | $2,400 | Business lines |\n| Miscellaneous | $350 | $4,200 | Supplies, subscriptions, bank fees |\n| **Total Fixed Costs** | **$12,500** | **$150,000** | |\n\n### Variable Costs (Per Project/Sale)\n\n| Category | Cost Basis | Notes |\n|----------|-----------|-------|\n| Contractor fees (3D design) | 25-30% of custom project revenue | Per-project basis |\n| Travel for on-site delivery | $500-$1,500 per district visit | Mileage, meals, occasionally hotel |\n| Demo equipment (VR headsets) | $300-$500 per headset, amortized | Loaner units for pilots |\n| Cloud hosting (per customer) | $15-$50/month per active district | AWS/Azure usage-based |\n| Payment processing | 2.5-3% of revenue | Credit card and ACH fees |\n\n### Contribution Margin by Product\n\n| Product | Avg Revenue | Variable Cost | Contribution Margin | CM % |\n|---------|------------|---------------|--------------------|----- |\n| Custom XR Experience | $25,000 | $8,750 | $16,250 | **65%** |\n| District Subscription | $6,500/yr | $1,300 | $5,200 | **80%** |\n| Professional Services | $3,000 | $1,800 | $1,200 | **40%** |\n| Pilot Program | $2,000 | $2,400 | ($400) | **-20%** |\n\nPilots operate at a loss by design -- they are a customer acquisition tool. The negative margin is recovered when pilots convert to subscriptions or custom projects (target 40% conversion rate).\n\n### Break-Even Calculation\n\nUsing the **weighted average contribution margin** based on expected revenue mix:\n\n- Expected mix: 40% Custom, 35% Subscription, 15% Services, 10% Pilots\n- Weighted CM% = (0.40 x 65%) + (0.35 x 80%) + (0.15 x 40%) + (0.10 x -20%) = 26% + 28% + 6% + (-2%) = **58%**\n\n**Break-Even Revenue = Fixed Costs / Weighted CM%**\n\nBreak-Even = $150,000 / 0.58 = **$258,621 annual revenue** or approximately **$21,552 per month**\n\n### Sensitivity Analysis\n\n| Scenario | Fixed Costs | CM% | Break-Even Revenue |\n|----------|-------------|-----|--------------------|\n| Base case | $150,000 | 58% | $258,621 |\n| Add full-time hire | $200,000 | 58% | $344,828 |\n| Higher subscription mix (50%) | $150,000 | 63% | $238,095 |\n| Lower custom margins (55%) | $150,000 | 54% | $277,778 |\n| Best case (lean + high sub mix) | $130,000 | 65% | $200,000 |\n\n### Path to Profitability Timeline\n\n- **Months 1-6**: Investment phase. Revenue $0-$5,000/month. Focus on product, first pilots, pipeline building.\n- **Months 7-12**: Traction phase. Revenue $5,000-$15,000/month. First subscription customers, 2-3 custom projects.\n- **Months 13-18**: Growth phase. Revenue $15,000-$25,000/month. **Break-even target: Month 15-18**.\n- **Months 19-24**: Scale phase. Revenue $25,000+/month. Profitable; reinvest in team and product.\n\nKey assumption: Reaching break-even requires approximately 8-10 active district subscription customers plus 4-6 custom projects per year.',
 ARRAY['break-even', 'contribution-margin', 'fixed-costs', 'variable-costs', 'profitability', 'sensitivity-analysis'],
 false, 6);


