-- TAXES 1: LLC Filing Requirements - Indiana
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'formation', 'LLC Filing Requirements - Indiana',
 'Step-by-step guide to forming an Indiana LLC including Articles of Organization, registered agent, EIN, and biennial reporting.',
 E'## LLC Filing Requirements - Indiana\n\nForming an LLC in Indiana is straightforward and can be completed online in under an hour. Here is the complete process with current fees and requirements.\n\n### Step 1: Choose a Business Name\n\n- Must include \"LLC,\" \"L.L.C.,\" or \"Limited Liability Company\"\n- Must be distinguishable from existing entities registered with the Indiana Secretary of State\n- Search availability at INBiz.in.gov (free search)\n- Optional: Reserve the name for 120 days ($20 fee)\n\n### Step 2: Appoint a Registered Agent\n\nEvery Indiana LLC must maintain a registered agent who:\n\n- Has a **physical street address in Indiana** (no P.O. boxes)\n- Is available during normal business hours to accept legal documents (service of process)\n- Can be an individual (yourself, if you have an IN address) or a registered agent service ($50-$300/year)\n- If you serve as your own agent, your home address becomes public record\n\n### Step 3: File Articles of Organization\n\n- File online at **INBiz.in.gov** (Indiana Secretary of State''s business portal)\n- Filing fee: **$95 online** ($100 by mail)\n- Required information: LLC name, registered agent name and address, principal office address, organizer name and address, management structure (member-managed or manager-managed)\n- Processing time: Online filings are typically processed within **24-48 hours** (often same-day)\n- You will receive a stamped copy of your Articles and a Certificate of Existence\n\n### Step 4: Create an Operating Agreement\n\nIndiana does **not** require you to file an operating agreement with the state, but you absolutely should create one. It:\n\n- Defines member ownership percentages and capital contributions\n- Establishes voting rights and decision-making procedures\n- Outlines profit and loss distribution\n- Covers member departure, death, or dissolution procedures\n- Protects your limited liability status (courts may \"pierce the veil\" without one)\n- Should be signed by all members and kept with company records\n\n### Step 5: Obtain an EIN (Employer Identification Number)\n\n- Apply online at **IRS.gov** using Form SS-4 (free, immediate issuance)\n- Required for: opening a business bank account, hiring employees, filing tax returns\n- Apply as a single-member LLC (disregarded entity) or multi-member LLC (partnership) depending on structure\n- You receive your EIN immediately upon completing the online application\n- Keep the EIN confirmation letter (CP 575) in your permanent records\n\n### Step 6: Register with Indiana DOR\n\n- File **Form BT-1** (Business Tax Application) with the Indiana Department of Revenue\n- Register through **INtax.in.gov** for state tax obligations\n- Registers you for: sales tax collection (if applicable), withholding tax (if you have employees), and other state taxes\n- No filing fee for BT-1\n\n### Step 7: Biennial Business Entity Report\n\n- Due every **two years** in the month your LLC was formed\n- Filing fee: **$31** (online via INBiz)\n- Reports current registered agent, principal office, and member/manager information\n- **Failure to file** results in administrative dissolution of the LLC after notice period\n- Set a calendar reminder; Indiana does not send courtesy reminders\n\n### Timeline Summary\n\n| Step | Time Required | Cost |\n|------|--------------|------|\n| Name search | 15 minutes | Free |\n| Articles of Organization | 30 minutes | $95 |\n| Operating Agreement | 2-5 hours (or hire attorney, ~$500-$1,500) | $0-$1,500 |\n| EIN Application | 15 minutes | Free |\n| BT-1 Registration | 20 minutes | Free |\n| Business bank account | 1-2 hours at the bank | Varies |\n| **Total** | **1-2 business days** | **$95 minimum** |',
 ARRAY['LLC', 'Indiana', 'formation', 'Articles-of-Organization', 'EIN', 'registered-agent', 'INBiz'],
 true, 10);

-- TAXES 2: C-Corp vs S-Corp vs LLC Comparison
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'entity-structure', 'C-Corp vs S-Corp vs LLC Tax Comparison',
 'Detailed comparison of entity types covering tax treatment, self-employment tax, QBI deduction, and the S-Corp salary threshold analysis.',
 E'## C-Corp vs S-Corp vs LLC Tax Comparison\n\nChoosing the right entity structure has significant tax implications. This analysis focuses on the practical differences for a small EdTech company in Indiana.\n\n### Tax Treatment Overview\n\n| Feature | Single-Member LLC | Multi-Member LLC | S-Corporation | C-Corporation |\n|---------|-------------------|-----------------|---------------|---------------|\n| Federal tax filing | Schedule C (Form 1040) | Form 1065 (K-1s to members) | Form 1120-S (K-1s to shareholders) | Form 1120 |\n| Entity-level federal tax | None (pass-through) | None (pass-through) | None (pass-through) | **21% corporate rate** |\n| Indiana entity tax | None (pass-through) | None (pass-through) | None (pass-through) | **4.9% corporate income tax** |\n| Self-employment tax | **15.3% on all profit** | **15.3% on all profit** | **Only on salary** | None (but double taxation) |\n| Dividend/distribution tax | N/A | N/A | N/A | **0-23.8% on dividends** |\n\n### Self-Employment Tax Deep Dive\n\nThe self-employment tax rate is **15.3%** (12.4% Social Security on first $168,600 of earnings in 2024 + 2.9% Medicare on all earnings, plus 0.9% Additional Medicare Tax on earnings above $200,000).\n\n- **LLC**: All net profit is subject to SE tax. If the LLC earns $100,000 in profit, SE tax = approximately $14,130.\n- **S-Corp**: Only the shareholder-employee''s **reasonable salary** is subject to payroll tax. Remaining profit passes through as a distribution not subject to SE tax.\n- **Example at $100K profit**: S-Corp pays $60,000 salary (SE tax ~$9,180) + $40,000 distribution (no SE tax) = **$9,180 total** vs. LLC''s $14,130. Savings: **$4,950/year**.\n\n### Qualified Business Income (QBI) Deduction\n\nSection 199A allows a **20% deduction on qualified business income** for pass-through entities (LLC and S-Corp):\n\n- Available to LLC members and S-Corp shareholders\n- **Not available** to C-Corp shareholders (C-Corps have their own lower rate)\n- Phase-out begins at $191,950 taxable income (single) / $383,900 (married filing jointly) for 2024\n- Specified Service Trade or Business (SSTB) limitations may apply -- technology consulting could be classified as SSTB, but software product sales generally are not\n- Effective benefit: If you have $80,000 QBI, the deduction is $16,000, saving roughly $3,520-$5,280 in federal taxes depending on bracket\n\n### Reasonable Salary Requirement (S-Corp)\n\nThe IRS requires S-Corp shareholder-employees to pay themselves a **\"reasonable salary\"** before taking distributions:\n\n- Must reflect what a comparable employee would earn in a similar role\n- For a startup CEO/founder doing technical + business work, $50,000-$80,000 is generally defensible depending on industry and geography\n- Setting salary too low is the #1 audit trigger for S-Corps\n- IRS looks at: job duties, experience, comparable wages in the area, company revenue and profitability\n- Safe harbor: salary should be at least 40-60% of total compensation (salary + distributions)\n\n### C-Corp Double Taxation\n\nC-Corp profits are taxed twice:\n\n1. **Corporate level**: 21% federal + 4.9% Indiana = 25.9% on corporate income\n2. **Shareholder level**: When profits are distributed as dividends, taxed at 0-23.8% (qualified dividend rates)\n- Effective combined rate on $100K profit: ~$25,900 corporate tax + ~$14,800 dividend tax on the remaining $74,100 = ~$40,700 total (40.7%)\n- Compare to S-Corp/LLC at 24% marginal bracket + 15.3% SE: ~$39,300 total but with QBI deduction potentially reducing to ~$35,000\n\n### When to Elect S-Corp Status\n\nThe S-Corp election (Form 2553) generally becomes beneficial when net business income consistently exceeds **~$50,000-$60,000 per year**. Below that threshold, the additional costs of S-Corp compliance eat into the SE tax savings:\n\n- Annual payroll processing: $500-$1,500/year\n- Additional tax return (Form 1120-S): $500-$1,500 preparation fee\n- Quarterly payroll tax filings: Time and/or preparer cost\n- Reasonable salary analysis and documentation\n\n**Rule of thumb**: If SE tax savings exceed $4,000-$5,000 annually (roughly $60K+ net income), the S-Corp election pays for itself.\n\n### Indiana-Specific Considerations\n\n- Indiana''s individual income tax rate is **3.05%** plus county tax (varies from 0.5% to 3.38% depending on county of residence)\n- Indiana''s corporate income tax rate is **4.9%** (with scheduled reductions in coming years)\n- Indiana conforms to federal S-Corp election -- no separate state election needed\n- LLC annual filing: Biennial report ($31); S-Corp: Biennial report ($31) + Form IT-20S state return\n- No franchise tax in Indiana for any entity type',
 ARRAY['entity-structure', 'LLC', 'S-Corp', 'C-Corp', 'self-employment-tax', 'QBI', 'reasonable-salary', 'Indiana'],
 true, 9);

-- TAXES 3: Indiana Corporate Tax
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'state-tax', 'Indiana Corporate & Individual Income Tax',
 'Indiana income tax rates, filing requirements, estimated payment schedules, nexus rules, and pass-through taxation mechanics.',
 E'## Indiana Corporate & Individual Income Tax\n\nIndiana has a relatively straightforward state tax system. Understanding the rates, filing requirements, and pass-through mechanics is essential for tax planning.\n\n### Corporate Income Tax (C-Corporations)\n\n- **Rate**: 4.9% of adjusted gross income apportioned to Indiana\n- Indiana has been gradually reducing its corporate rate (was 8.5% in 2012, 5.25% in 2022, 4.9% in 2023+)\n- Filed on **Form IT-20** (Indiana Corporate Income Tax Return)\n- Due on the **15th day of the 4th month** after the close of the tax year (April 15 for calendar-year filers)\n- Estimated payments required if tax liability exceeds $2,500\n\n### Individual Income Tax (Pass-Through Entities)\n\nFor LLCs and S-Corps, income passes through to the individual owners:\n\n- **State rate**: 3.05% of adjusted gross income (2024)\n- **County tax**: Additional 0.5% to 3.38% depending on county of residence\n  - Marion County (Indianapolis): 2.02%\n  - Hamilton County (Carmel/Fishers): 1.62%\n  - Allen County (Fort Wayne): 1.48%\n  - Tippecanoe County (Lafayette): 1.11%\n  - Monroe County (Bloomington): 1.345%\n- Combined state + county rate typically ranges from 3.55% to 6.43%\n- Filed on **Form IT-40** (individual) with Schedule IT-40 for business income\n\n### Estimated Payment Schedule\n\nIndiana estimated payments follow the federal schedule:\n\n| Payment | Due Date | Percentage |\n|---------|----------|------------|\n| 1st Quarter | April 15 | 25% of estimated annual liability |\n| 2nd Quarter | June 15 | 25% |\n| 3rd Quarter | September 15 | 25% |\n| 4th Quarter | January 15 (following year) | 25% |\n\n- Use **Form ES-40** for individual estimated payments\n- Use **Form IT-20ES** for corporate estimated payments\n- Pay online through **INtax.in.gov** or via INTIME (Indiana Taxpayer Information Management Engine)\n- Penalty for underpayment: 10% of the underpaid amount\n\n### Nexus Rules\n\nA business has Indiana tax nexus (filing obligation) if it has:\n\n- **Physical presence**: Office, employees, inventory, or property in Indiana\n- **Economic nexus**: Exceeds $100,000 in Indiana-sourced gross receipts\n- **Factor presence**: Exceeds threshold of any apportionment factor (property, payroll, or sales) in Indiana\n\nFor Ascent XR, headquartered in Indiana, nexus is automatic. The question becomes whether activities in other states create nexus there (see Multi-State Tax Nexus article).\n\n### Composite Return Option\n\nFor multi-member LLCs or S-Corps with nonresident members:\n\n- Indiana allows filing a **composite return** (Form IT-65COMP) on behalf of nonresident members\n- The entity pays the tax at the highest individual rate (3.05% state + applicable county rate)\n- This simplifies compliance for nonresident members who would otherwise need to file individual Indiana returns\n- All nonresident members must consent to be included\n\n### LLC Pass-Through Mechanics\n\n- **Single-member LLC**: Disregarded for federal purposes; reported on Schedule C. Indiana follows federal treatment. No separate state entity return required.\n- **Multi-member LLC**: Treated as partnership for federal purposes; files Form 1065 federally and **Form IT-65** with Indiana. Issues Schedule IN K-1 to each member.\n- **LLC electing S-Corp**: Files Form 1120-S federally and **Form IT-20S** with Indiana. Issues Schedule IN K-1 to each shareholder.\n- In all pass-through cases, the income flows to the member''s individual return and is taxed at the individual rate plus county rate.',
 ARRAY['Indiana', 'corporate-tax', 'individual-income-tax', 'county-tax', 'estimated-payments', 'nexus', 'pass-through'],
 false, 8);

-- TAXES 4: Indiana Sales Tax for SaaS
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'state-tax', 'Indiana Sales Tax for SaaS Products',
 'Indiana sales tax treatment of SaaS, educational institution exemptions, exemption certificates, and collection requirements.',
 E'## Indiana Sales Tax for SaaS Products\n\nSaaS taxation is one of the most complex areas of state tax law, and Indiana''s position is particularly important for Ascent XR since it is the home state.\n\n### Indiana''s Position on SaaS\n\nIndiana imposes a **7% sales tax** on SaaS. The Indiana Department of Revenue has ruled that SaaS constitutes the transfer of **tangible personal property** delivered electronically, making it subject to sales tax under IC 6-2.5-4-1. Key rulings:\n\n- **Revenue Ruling #2020-02ST**: Confirmed that remotely accessed software (SaaS) is taxable as a retail transaction\n- The taxable event is the right to access and use the software, not the delivery of a physical product\n- This applies regardless of whether the customer downloads anything; mere access through a browser qualifies\n- Indiana is one of approximately 20 states that explicitly tax SaaS\n\n### Educational Institution Exemptions\n\nSchool districts in Indiana are **exempt from sales tax** under IC 6-2.5-5-25 (government entity exemption) and IC 6-2.5-5-26 (educational institution exemption):\n\n- **Public school districts**: Exempt as government entities. Must provide a completed **Form ST-105** (Indiana General Sales Tax Exemption Certificate).\n- **Private schools (501(c)(3))**: Exempt as nonprofit educational institutions. Also use Form ST-105.\n- **Ascent XR action**: Collect a completed ST-105 from every school district customer **before the first invoice**. Keep these certificates on file permanently -- you must produce them upon audit.\n- If a customer fails to provide an exemption certificate, you are required to collect and remit the 7% sales tax.\n\n### Exemption Certificate Requirements (Form ST-105)\n\nA valid ST-105 must include:\n\n1. Purchaser''s name and address\n2. Description of property being purchased (\"SaaS educational technology platform\")\n3. Reason for exemption (check the appropriate box -- typically \"Government\" or \"Educational\")\n4. Purchaser''s signature and date\n5. Indiana Taxpayer Identification Number (TID) or Federal ID\n\nAccept blanket certificates covering all future purchases from that district. Single-purchase certificates are also valid but require new documentation for each transaction.\n\n### Resale Certificates\n\nIf a reseller (e.g., an IT distributor or VAR) purchases Ascent XR licenses for resale to districts:\n\n- They provide a **Form ST-105** with \"Resale\" checked\n- You do not collect sales tax on the sale to the reseller\n- The reseller is responsible for collecting sales tax from the end customer (or accepting their exemption certificate)\n\n### Bundled Transaction Rules\n\nIf Ascent XR sells a bundle that includes taxable items (software) and non-taxable items (professional services):\n\n- If the bundle is sold for **one non-itemized price**, Indiana''s bundled transaction rules under IC 6-2.5-1-11.5 apply\n- If the taxable items are more than **incidental** (more than 10% of the price), the **entire transaction** may be taxable\n- **Best practice**: Always itemize invoices with separate line items for software/SaaS and services to ensure only the taxable portion is subject to sales tax\n\n### Digital Goods Taxation\n\nBeyond SaaS, Indiana taxes other digital products relevant to Ascent XR:\n\n- Downloaded software: Taxable\n- Digital educational content: Taxable (unless purchased by exempt entity)\n- Streaming/hosted content: Taxable as specified digital product\n- Custom software development: Generally **exempt** as a professional service, but must be truly custom (not a configuration of existing product)\n\n### Collection and Remittance via INtax\n\n- Register for sales tax collection via **Form BT-1** on INtax.in.gov\n- File **Form ST-103** (Sales Tax Return) monthly, quarterly, or annually depending on volume:\n  - Monthly: If average monthly tax collected exceeds $1,000\n  - Quarterly: If average monthly tax is $75-$1,000\n  - Annually: If average monthly tax is under $75\n- Returns are due on the **20th of the month** following the reporting period\n- Pay electronically through INtax or INTIME\n- Retain all exemption certificates, returns, and supporting documentation for **at least 3 years** (Indiana statute of limitations for sales tax audits)',
 ARRAY['sales-tax', 'SaaS', 'Indiana', 'exemptions', 'ST-105', 'school-districts', 'digital-goods', 'INtax'],
 false, 8);

-- TAXES 5: Indiana Business Personal Property Tax
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'state-tax', 'Indiana Business Personal Property Tax',
 'Form 103 filing requirements, depreciation schedules, thresholds, and appeal processes for business personal property in Indiana.',
 E'## Indiana Business Personal Property Tax\n\nIndiana is one of the states that taxes business personal property (equipment, furniture, computers). While Indiana has been phasing out this tax for small businesses, it is important to understand the rules.\n\n### What Is Business Personal Property?\n\nBusiness personal property includes all tangible assets used in your business that are not real estate:\n\n- Computers, monitors, peripherals\n- VR/XR headsets and development equipment\n- Office furniture (desks, chairs, shelving)\n- Software (purchased, not SaaS subscriptions)\n- Vehicles titled in the business name\n- Trade fixtures and leasehold improvements\n\n### Filing Requirements\n\n- File **Form 103** (Business Tangible Personal Property Return) with your county assessor\n- **Due date**: May 15 annually\n- Lists all personal property owned on **January 1** of the assessment year (assessment date)\n- Must report property at **cost** (original acquisition price) -- not current market value\n- Indiana uses statutory depreciation tables (not IRS depreciation) to determine assessed value\n\n### Depreciation Schedules\n\nIndiana uses its own depreciation schedules, published in the Real Property Assessment Guidelines:\n\n| Asset Type | Useful Life | Year 1 | Year 2 | Year 3 | Year 4 | Year 5+ |\n|-----------|-------------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|\n| Computers & peripherals | 4 years | 75% | 56% | 42% | 30% | 30% (floor) |\n| Software (purchased) | 3 years | 67% | 44% | 30% | 30% | 30% (floor) |\n| Office furniture | 10 years | 90% | 81% | 73% | 66% | Declining to 30% floor |\n| Vehicles | 5 years | 80% | 64% | 51% | 41% | 30% floor |\n| Telecom equipment | 6 years | 83% | 69% | 58% | 48% | Declining to 30% floor |\n\nThe minimum (floor) assessed value is **30%** of original cost regardless of actual depreciation.\n\n### Filing Threshold\n\nIndiana provides a **$80,000 assessed value** personal property tax exemption for businesses:\n\n- If the total assessed value of all your business personal property in a county is **under $80,000**, you owe **no personal property tax**\n- You must still file Form 103 to claim the exemption\n- If your assessed value exceeds $80,000, you are taxed on the **entire amount** (not just the excess over $80K)\n- For a startup with $20,000-$40,000 in equipment at cost, the assessed value after depreciation will likely fall under the threshold\n\n### Tax Rate and Calculation\n\nIf you exceed the exemption threshold:\n\n- The tax rate varies by taxing district (county, city, township, school district)\n- Typical effective rates range from **$1.50 to $3.50 per $100 of assessed value**\n- Example: $120,000 assessed value x $2.50/$100 = $3,000 annual property tax\n- Bills are typically sent in spring with payment due in **May and November** (two installments)\n\n### Appeal Process\n\nIf you believe your assessed value is incorrect:\n\n1. **Informal conference**: Contact the county assessor within 45 days of the assessment notice. Many issues are resolved here.\n2. **Form 130 (Petition to the County Property Tax Assessment Board of Appeals - PTABOA)**: File within 45 days of the informal conference decision\n3. **Indiana Board of Tax Review**: Appeal PTABOA decisions within 30 days\n4. **Indiana Tax Court**: Final level of appeal\n\nCommon grounds for appeal: incorrect cost basis reported, wrong depreciation schedule applied, property was disposed of before assessment date.\n\n### Audit Triggers\n\n- Filing a return showing significantly less property than prior year without explanation\n- Not filing at all (county assessors cross-reference business registrations)\n- Reporting zero or minimal property when the business appears active\n- Inconsistencies between reported property and other filings (insurance declarations, financial statements)',
 ARRAY['personal-property-tax', 'Form-103', 'Indiana', 'depreciation', 'assessment', 'exemption-threshold'],
 false, 6);

-- TAXES 6: Indiana DOR Requirements
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'compliance', 'Indiana Department of Revenue - Registration & Requirements',
 'Complete guide to Indiana DOR registration, INtax setup, withholding requirements, unemployment tax, and penalty rates.',
 E'## Indiana Department of Revenue - Registration & Requirements\n\nEvery Indiana business must register with the Indiana Department of Revenue (DOR) and comply with ongoing filing requirements. This article covers the complete setup and maintenance process.\n\n### BT-1 Business Tax Application\n\nForm BT-1 is the master registration form for all Indiana state taxes:\n\n- File online at **INtax.in.gov** (preferred) or submit a paper form\n- Registers you for applicable taxes: sales tax, withholding tax, food and beverage tax, county innkeeper''s tax, etc.\n- Separate sections for each tax type; complete only the sections that apply\n- No filing fee\n- Processing time: Online applications typically processed within 3-5 business days\n- Upon approval, you receive your **Indiana Taxpayer Identification Number (TID)**\n\n### INtax / INTIME Online System\n\nIndiana has transitioned from INtax to **INTIME (Indiana Taxpayer Information Management Engine)** at intime.dor.in.gov:\n\n- File and pay all state taxes electronically\n- View account balances and payment history\n- Receive electronic notices and correspondence\n- Manage multiple business accounts under one login\n- Set up automatic payments for recurring obligations\n- **Required**: Electronic filing is mandatory for most business tax returns\n\n### Withholding Tax Requirements (WH-1)\n\nIf you have employees (including yourself as an S-Corp shareholder-employee):\n\n- Register for withholding tax via BT-1\n- Withhold Indiana state tax (3.05%) and applicable county tax from employee wages\n- File **Form WH-1** (Withholding Tax Return):\n  - **Monthly**: If average monthly withholding exceeds $1,000 (due on the 30th of the following month)\n  - **Quarterly**: If average monthly withholding is under $1,000 (due on the last day of the month following the quarter)\n- File annual reconciliation **Form WH-3** by January 31, reporting all wages and withholding for the prior year\n- Issue Indiana Form W-2s to employees by January 31\n\n### Unemployment Tax (UI)\n\n- Register with the **Indiana Department of Workforce Development (DWD)** -- separate from DOR\n- New employer rate: **2.5%** of the first $9,500 in wages per employee per year\n- Rate adjusts after you have experience (claims history); ranges from 0.5% to 7.4%\n- File quarterly wage reports via **Uplink** (employer.dwd.in.gov)\n- Due dates: April 30, July 31, October 31, January 31\n- Maximum annual UI tax per employee: $237.50 (at 2.5% rate)\n\n### Estimated Payment Schedule\n\nFor income tax (pass-through entities filing individual returns):\n\n- **April 15**: 1st quarter estimated payment\n- **June 15**: 2nd quarter estimated payment  \n- **September 15**: 3rd quarter estimated payment\n- **January 15**: 4th quarter estimated payment\n- Use **Form ES-40** or pay directly through INTIME\n- Safe harbor: Pay at least 100% of prior year''s Indiana tax liability to avoid penalties\n\n### Annual Return Deadlines\n\n| Return | Entity Type | Due Date | Extension |\n|--------|------------|----------|----------|\n| Form IT-40 | Individual / SMLLC | April 15 | October 15 (automatic with federal extension) |\n| Form IT-65 | Partnership / Multi-member LLC | April 15 | September 15 |\n| Form IT-20S | S-Corporation | April 15 | September 15 |\n| Form IT-20 | C-Corporation | April 15 (calendar year) | October 15 |\n| Form ST-103 | Sales Tax (annual filers) | January 31 | No extension |\n\n### Penalty Rates\n\n- **Late filing penalty**: 10% of the tax due (minimum $5)\n- **Late payment penalty**: 10% of the unpaid tax\n- **Interest**: Accrues on unpaid tax from the original due date at a rate set annually by DOR (currently approximately 5-6%)\n- **Fraud penalty**: 100% of the unpaid tax for fraudulent returns\n- Penalties can be abated for reasonable cause (first-time penalty abatement, natural disaster, etc.) by filing a written protest\n\n### Voluntary Disclosure Agreements (VDA)\n\nIf you discover you should have been filing Indiana returns but were not:\n\n- Contact the DOR to enter a **Voluntary Disclosure Agreement**\n- Typical terms: File returns for the last 3-4 years (shorter than the full statute of limitations)\n- Penalties are waived; you pay only the tax due plus interest\n- Must not have been contacted by DOR about the liability prior to initiating the VDA\n- Can be negotiated through the Indiana DOR''s Taxpayer Advocate Office',
 ARRAY['Indiana-DOR', 'BT-1', 'INtax', 'INTIME', 'withholding', 'WH-1', 'unemployment', 'penalties'],
 false, 7);

-- TAXES 7: Federal Tax Deadlines & Quarterly Estimates
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'deadlines', 'Federal Tax Deadlines & Quarterly Estimated Payments',
 'Complete federal estimated tax payment schedule, safe harbor rules, EFTPS setup, penalty calculations, and extension procedures.',
 E'## Federal Tax Deadlines & Quarterly Estimated Payments\n\nAs a pass-through entity owner, you are responsible for making quarterly estimated tax payments to the IRS. Missing these deadlines results in penalties that compound throughout the year.\n\n### Form 1040-ES Payment Schedule\n\n| Payment | Period Covered | Due Date | Notes |\n|---------|---------------|----------|-------|\n| Q1 | January 1 - March 31 | **April 15** | Also the annual return due date |\n| Q2 | April 1 - May 31 | **June 15** | Only covers 2 months, not 3 |\n| Q3 | June 1 - August 31 | **September 15** | Covers 3 months |\n| Q4 | September 1 - December 31 | **January 15** (following year) | Covers 4 months |\n\nIf the due date falls on a weekend or federal holiday, the deadline moves to the next business day.\n\n### Safe Harbor Rules\n\nYou can avoid underpayment penalties by meeting either safe harbor:\n\n1. **100% of prior year tax**: Pay at least 100% of your total tax liability from the previous year, divided into four equal installments. This works even if your current-year income increases dramatically.\n2. **110% rule for high earners**: If your AGI exceeded **$150,000** ($75,000 if married filing separately) in the prior year, you must pay **110%** of prior year tax to use this safe harbor.\n3. **90% of current year**: Pay at least 90% of your current-year tax liability through estimates and withholding.\n\n**Best strategy for a startup**: In year one with no prior-year tax history, use the annualized income installment method (Form 2210 Schedule AI) to minimize estimates during months with low or no revenue.\n\n### EFTPS (Electronic Federal Tax Payment System)\n\n- Enroll at **eftps.gov** or by calling 1-800-555-4477\n- Enrollment takes **5-7 business days** (PIN is mailed)\n- Allows you to schedule payments up to 365 days in advance\n- Tracks all payment history -- essential for audit documentation\n- Required for businesses with annual federal tax deposits of $200,000+\n- Recommended for all businesses for convenience and proof of payment\n- Payments must be scheduled by **8:00 PM ET** the business day before the due date\n\n### Penalty Calculation\n\nThe underpayment penalty is calculated using the **federal short-term rate plus 3 percentage points**, assessed quarterly:\n\n- Current annualized penalty rate: approximately **8%** (varies by quarter as rates change)\n- Penalty is calculated on each missed or insufficient quarterly payment from its due date to the date paid or April 15 of the following year\n- **Example**: If you owe $5,000 for Q1 and pay nothing until April 15 of the following year, the penalty is approximately $5,000 x 8% x (12/12) = $400\n- The penalty applies separately to each quarter''s underpayment\n- Form 2210 is used to calculate the penalty or request a waiver\n\n### Estimated Payment Worksheet\n\nTo calculate your quarterly estimates:\n\n1. Estimate total annual income from all sources\n2. Subtract estimated deductions (standard or itemized) and QBI deduction\n3. Calculate tax using current brackets (10%, 12%, 22%, 24%, 32%, 35%, 37%)\n4. Add self-employment tax (if applicable): 15.3% on 92.35% of net self-employment income\n5. Subtract any expected withholding (W-2 income, if applicable)\n6. Subtract any credits (R&D, child tax, etc.)\n7. Divide the remaining liability by 4 for equal quarterly payments\n8. **Pro tip**: Use IRS Form 1040-ES worksheet or tax software (TurboTax, QuickBooks) to automate this calculation\n\n### Special First-Year Rules\n\n- No penalty for the first year if you had no prior-year tax liability **and** were a U.S. citizen/resident for the entire prior year\n- However, you still owe the tax -- just no penalty for not making estimates\n- If you expect to owe $1,000 or more in tax after withholding, you should make estimates regardless\n\n### Extension Procedures\n\n**Individual (Form 4868)**:\n- Grants an automatic **6-month extension** (to October 15)\n- **Does not extend the payment deadline** -- you must still pay estimated tax by April 15\n- File electronically through IRS Free File or tax software\n\n**Business Returns (Form 7004)**:\n- S-Corp (Form 1120-S): Automatic 6-month extension to September 15\n- Partnership (Form 1065): Automatic 6-month extension to September 15\n- C-Corp (Form 1120): Automatic 6-month extension to October 15\n- File Form 7004 by the original due date of the return',
 ARRAY['federal-taxes', 'estimated-payments', '1040-ES', 'EFTPS', 'safe-harbor', 'deadlines', 'penalties', 'extensions'],
 false, 9);

-- TAXES 8: R&D Tax Credits for Tech Startups
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'credits', 'R&D Tax Credits for Technology Startups',
 'Section 41 federal R&D credit, qualified research activities for XR/software, startup payroll credit election, documentation requirements, and Indiana R&D credit.',
 E'## R&D Tax Credits for Technology Startups\n\nThe R&D tax credit is one of the most valuable and most underutilized tax incentives for tech startups. Ascent XR''s software development and XR content creation activities likely qualify.\n\n### Section 41 Credit Overview\n\nThe federal Research and Experimentation credit (Section 41 of the Internal Revenue Code) provides a credit against income tax for increases in qualified research expenditures. Two calculation methods:\n\n1. **Regular Credit**: 20% of qualified research expenses (QREs) exceeding a base amount (calculated from historical research spending as a percentage of gross receipts)\n2. **Alternative Simplified Credit (ASC)**: 14% of QREs exceeding 50% of the average QREs for the three preceding tax years. Most startups use this method because they lack the historical data for the regular credit.\n\nFor a startup with no prior research history, the ASC provides a credit equal to **6% of current-year QREs** (14% x QREs - 14% x 50% x $0 = 6% net, since the base is zero for the first three years).\n\n### Qualified Research Activities (QRA) for XR/Software\n\nTo qualify under the **four-part test**, an activity must meet ALL of the following:\n\n1. **Technological Uncertainty**: The development involves uncertainty about the capability, method, or design. For Ascent XR: developing new XR interaction models for K-12 students, optimizing rendering performance for school-grade hardware, creating adaptive learning algorithms.\n\n2. **Process of Experimentation**: Systematic evaluation of alternatives through modeling, simulation, testing, or trial and error. For Ascent XR: A/B testing different UI designs for student engagement, iterating on 3D environment performance, testing compatibility across VR headset models.\n\n3. **Technical in Nature**: Relies on hard sciences -- engineering, computer science, physics, mathematics. Software development inherently qualifies. XR development involves computer graphics, spatial computing, and interaction design.\n\n4. **Qualified Purpose**: The research aims to create a new or improved product, process, or technique. For Ascent XR: building the platform, improving user experience, developing new XR content types.\n\n**Activities that typically qualify at Ascent XR**:\n- Core platform development (Unity/Unreal engine work, backend API development)\n- 3D environment and content creation requiring technical problem-solving\n- Performance optimization for target hardware\n- Assessment and analytics engine development\n- Integration development (LMS, SIS, authentication systems)\n\n**Activities that do NOT qualify**:\n- Marketing and sales activities\n- General business administration\n- Routine data entry or content loading\n- Research conducted after the product is commercially available (routine improvements)\n- Market research or customer surveys\n\n### Form 6765 Filing\n\n- File **Form 6765** (Credit for Increasing Research Activities) with your tax return\n- Elect the Alternative Simplified Credit method on Line 24\n- Report total QREs broken down by: wages, supplies, and contract research\n- Attach detailed calculation supporting the credit amount\n\n### $250K Payroll Tax Credit for Startups\n\nThis is the game-changer for pre-revenue and early-revenue startups:\n\n- Under Section 41(h), a **qualified small business** can elect to apply up to **$250,000** of the R&D credit against **payroll taxes** (employer portion of Social Security) instead of income taxes\n- **Qualifications**: Gross receipts under $5 million in the credit year AND less than 5 years of gross receipts history\n- This means you get the credit **even if you have no income tax liability** (which is common for startups)\n- Make the election on Form 6765, Part III\n- The credit offsets the employer''s 6.2% Social Security tax starting the quarter after the return is filed\n- Can be claimed for up to 5 consecutive years\n\n**Example for Ascent XR**: If you have $200,000 in qualified wages and use the ASC method, the credit is approximately $12,000 (6% x $200,000). Electing the payroll tax credit means $12,000 in cash savings against quarterly payroll tax deposits.\n\n### Documentation Requirements\n\nThe IRS is aggressive in auditing R&D credits. **Contemporaneous documentation** is critical:\n\n- **Project tracking**: Maintain records of each project''s technical goals, uncertainties, and experiments. Use Jira, GitHub issues, or similar tools with detailed descriptions.\n- **Time tracking**: Developers should log hours by project with brief descriptions of technical work performed. Tools like Harvest or Toggl work well.\n- **Technical notes**: Save design documents, architecture decisions, performance benchmarking results, bug reports reflecting technical challenges\n- **Financial records**: Separate QREs by category (wages, supplies, contract research) in your accounting system\n- **Employee statements**: Annual statements from technical staff describing the research activities they performed\n\n### Indiana R&D Credit\n\nIndiana offers an **additional 15%** credit on qualified research expenses incurred in Indiana:\n\n- Claimed on Form IT-20 (corporations) or Schedule IN-RD (individuals/pass-through entities)\n- This is **on top of** the federal credit -- you can claim both\n- Indiana credit = 15% x QREs performed in Indiana\n- Can be carried forward for unused credits\n- Combined federal + state R&D credit can reduce effective cost of R&D by 20-25%\n\n### Qualified Research Expenses Calculation\n\n| Category | What Counts | Example for Ascent XR |\n|----------|------------|----------------------|\n| Wages | W-2 wages for employees performing or supervising qualified research | Developer salary, CTO time allocation |\n| Supplies | Tangible property used in research (consumed) | VR headsets used exclusively for testing, cloud computing costs for dev/test environments |\n| Contract Research | 65% of amounts paid to contractors for qualified research | 65% of payments to contract developers working on platform features |\n\n**Note**: Only 65% of contract research payments count as QREs (not 100%), which is why in-house development generates a larger credit per dollar spent.',
 ARRAY['R&D-credit', 'Section-41', 'Form-6765', 'payroll-tax-credit', 'qualified-research', 'Indiana-R&D', 'documentation'],
 false, 9);

-- TAXES 9: Startup Tax Provisions
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'deductions', 'Startup Tax Deductions & Provisions',
 'Key tax deductions for startups including Section 195 startup costs, Section 179, bonus depreciation, home office, vehicle, and meal deductions.',
 E'## Startup Tax Deductions & Provisions\n\nStartups have access to several powerful tax deductions. Understanding these provisions from day one ensures you capture every deduction and structure expenses optimally.\n\n### Section 195: Startup Costs\n\nCosts incurred before your business begins active operations can be deducted under Section 195:\n\n- **Immediate deduction**: Up to **$5,000** in the first year of business\n- **Phase-out**: The $5,000 deduction is reduced dollar-for-dollar for startup costs exceeding $50,000\n- **Amortization**: Remaining startup costs are amortized over **180 months** (15 years) beginning in the month active business starts\n- **What qualifies**: Market research, travel to find suppliers/customers, advertising to open the business, salaries/wages for training employees, consultant fees for setting up the business\n- **What does NOT qualify**: Costs that would be deductible as ordinary business expenses once the business is operating (these are just normal deductions, not startup costs)\n- **Example**: $15,000 in pre-launch costs. Deduct $5,000 immediately, amortize the remaining $10,000 over 180 months ($55.56/month = $667/year)\n\n### Section 179 Equipment Expensing\n\nInstead of depreciating equipment over its useful life, Section 179 allows immediate expensing:\n\n- **2024 limit**: Up to **$1,160,000** in qualifying equipment can be deducted in the year of purchase\n- **Phase-out**: Begins when total equipment purchases exceed $2,890,000\n- **Qualifying property**: Computers, VR headsets, office furniture, software (off-the-shelf), vehicles (with limitations), equipment\n- **Limitation**: Cannot create a loss -- the deduction is limited to your taxable business income\n- **Example**: Purchase $8,000 in computers and VR development equipment. Deduct the entire $8,000 in year one instead of depreciating over 5 years.\n\n### Bonus Depreciation\n\nFor assets that don''t qualify for Section 179 or exceed the income limitation:\n\n- **2024**: 60% bonus depreciation (first-year deduction on the depreciable basis)\n- **2025**: 40% bonus depreciation\n- **2026**: 20% bonus depreciation\n- **2027+**: 0% (bonus depreciation phases out completely)\n- Unlike Section 179, bonus depreciation **can** create a net operating loss (NOL)\n- Applies automatically unless you elect out on a class-by-class basis\n- **Strategy**: Use Section 179 first (limited to income), then bonus depreciation for the remainder\n\n### Home Office Deduction\n\nIf you work from home, you can deduct a portion of home expenses:\n\n**Simplified Method**:\n- **$5 per square foot** of dedicated office space\n- Maximum: 300 square feet = **$1,500 annual deduction**\n- No need to track actual home expenses\n- Cannot generate a loss\n\n**Regular Method**:\n- Calculate the percentage of home used exclusively and regularly for business (square footage basis)\n- Apply that percentage to: mortgage interest/rent, property taxes, utilities, insurance, repairs, depreciation\n- More complex but often yields a larger deduction\n- **Example**: 200 sq ft office / 2,000 sq ft home = 10%. Annual home costs $24,000 x 10% = $2,400 deduction\n\n**Important**: The space must be used **exclusively and regularly** for business. A desk in the corner of a bedroom that''s also used personally does not qualify.\n\n### Vehicle Deduction\n\nTwo methods for business vehicle use:\n\n**Standard Mileage Rate**:\n- **2024**: 67 cents per business mile\n- Track all business miles with a log (date, destination, purpose, miles)\n- Include trips to client sites, conferences, office supply stores, bank, post office\n- Commuting miles (home to regular office) do NOT count, but if your home office is your principal place of business, trips to client sites qualify from home\n- Apps like MileIQ or Everlance automate tracking\n\n**Actual Expense Method**:\n- Deduct the business-use percentage of all vehicle costs: gas, insurance, repairs, depreciation, registration\n- Requires detailed records of total miles and business miles\n- Generally better for expensive vehicles or high-maintenance vehicles\n\n### Business Meals\n\n- **50%** of business meal costs are deductible (the 100% restaurant meal deduction expired after 2022)\n- Must be directly related to or associated with business (client meeting, team working lunch, business travel meals)\n- Must document: date, attendees, business purpose, amount, restaurant name\n- Per diem rates are available as an alternative for business travel\n- **Not deductible**: Entertainment expenses (sporting events, concerts) -- no longer deductible since TCJA\n\n### Organizational Costs (Section 248)\n\nSimilar to Section 195 but for costs of forming the entity itself:\n\n- **Immediate deduction**: Up to **$5,000** (reduced for costs over $50,000)\n- **Amortize remainder** over 180 months\n- **Qualifies**: State filing fees, legal fees for operating agreement, initial registered agent fees, organizational meeting costs\n\n### Legal and Accounting Startup Costs\n\n- Attorney fees for entity formation: Organizational cost (Section 248)\n- Attorney fees for contracts/IP: Section 195 startup cost or current business expense\n- Accountant fees for tax planning: Section 195 if pre-launch, ordinary deduction if post-launch\n- CPA fees for tax return preparation: Ordinary deduction in the year incurred\n- **Tip**: Engage tax and legal advisors before officially starting the business so their fees qualify under Section 195 or 248 for immediate deduction',
 ARRAY['startup-costs', 'Section-195', 'Section-179', 'bonus-depreciation', 'home-office', 'vehicle-deduction', 'meals', 'organizational-costs'],
 false, 7);

-- TAXES 10: State Deductions & Credits - Indiana
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'credits', 'State Deductions & Credits - Indiana',
 'Indiana-specific tax credits including R&D, EDGE, venture capital, Hoosier Business Investment, and headquarters relocation credits.',
 E'## State Deductions & Credits - Indiana\n\nIndiana offers several business tax credits that can significantly reduce state tax liability. For a tech startup, the R&D and economic development credits are particularly relevant.\n\n### Indiana Research & Development Credit\n\n- **Credit rate**: 15% of qualified research expenses (QREs) conducted in Indiana\n- This is **in addition to** the federal R&D credit -- you can claim both on the same expenses\n- Claimed on **Schedule IN-RD** (attached to IT-20, IT-20S, or IT-65)\n- **Carryforward**: Unused credits can be carried forward for up to 10 years\n- **No carryback** allowed\n- Must maintain records of Indiana-based research activities separately from total company research\n- **Example**: $150,000 in Indiana QREs x 15% = $22,500 state credit, plus the federal credit on the same expenses\n\n### EDGE Credit (Economic Development for a Growing Economy)\n\nThe EDGE credit is Indiana''s premier job creation incentive:\n\n- Provides a **refundable tax credit** equal to a percentage of payroll taxes on new jobs created\n- Typical credit: 50-100% of state income tax withholdings on new qualifying jobs for up to 10 years\n- **Requirements**: Create new, full-time jobs in Indiana with wages above the county average\n- Apply through the **Indiana Economic Development Corporation (IEDC)** before hiring\n- Must meet job creation and wage commitments over the agreement term\n- Credits are performance-based; you only receive them as jobs are actually created and maintained\n- **Best for**: Companies planning to hire 5+ employees within 2-3 years\n- Application involves business plan review, job creation projections, and investment commitments\n\n### Venture Capital Investment Credit (VCI)\n\nFor investors in Indiana-based companies:\n\n- **Credit rate**: 20% of qualified investment in a certified Indiana company\n- Maximum credit: **$1 million per investor per year**\n- The investee company must be certified by the IEDC as a qualified Indiana business\n- Company must have less than $10 million in annual revenue\n- Company must be headquartered in Indiana and have at least 50% of employees in Indiana\n- **Ascent XR application**: If raising investment, help investors claim this credit as an incentive -- effectively makes their investment 20% cheaper\n- Investors apply through IEDC; limited pool of credits available statewide each year ($12.5 million annual cap)\n\n### Hoosier Business Investment (HBI) Tax Credit\n\nFor businesses making significant capital investments in Indiana:\n\n- Credit against state tax liability based on qualifying capital investment\n- Typical credit: **10-25%** of capital investment, depending on project size and location\n- Qualifying investments: equipment, facilities, infrastructure related to the business\n- Minimum investment thresholds vary by project type and county\n- Apply through the IEDC before making the investment\n- Credits vest over time as investment commitments are met\n- **For Ascent XR**: Most relevant if establishing a dedicated office/studio with significant equipment investment ($100K+)\n\n### Headquarters Relocation Credit\n\nIndiana offers incentives for companies relocating their headquarters to Indiana:\n\n- Tax credit based on payroll and investment associated with the relocation\n- Must relocate executive and management functions to Indiana\n- Apply through IEDC before relocating\n- **For Ascent XR**: Not applicable if already headquartered in Indiana, but relevant if competitors or partner companies consider relocating\n\n### How to Claim Credits\n\n**On Corporate Returns (IT-20)**:\n- Complete the applicable credit schedule (Schedule IN-RD, Schedule IN-EDGE, etc.)\n- Enter the total credit on the IT-20 credits summary section\n- Apply against Indiana adjusted gross income tax liability\n\n**On Individual Returns (IT-40)**:\n- Credits from pass-through entities are reported on the Schedule IT-40 credits section\n- Use the amounts shown on your Indiana Schedule K-1 from the LLC or S-Corp\n- Same credit schedules must be completed and attached\n\n**On S-Corp Returns (IT-20S) / Partnership Returns (IT-65)**:\n- Credits are calculated at the entity level\n- Allocated to shareholders/members on Schedule IN K-1\n- Each shareholder/member claims their share on their individual IT-40\n\n### Carryforward Rules\n\n| Credit | Carryforward Period | Carryback |\n|--------|--------------------|-----------|\n| R&D Credit | 10 years | Not allowed |\n| EDGE Credit | Per agreement terms | Not allowed |\n| VCI Credit | 5 years | Not allowed |\n| HBI Credit | Per agreement terms | Not allowed |\n\nAlways claim credits in the earliest year possible. Track carryforward balances in a credit tracking spreadsheet and reconcile annually.',
 ARRAY['Indiana-credits', 'R&D-credit', 'EDGE', 'venture-capital', 'HBI', 'headquarters-relocation', 'IEDC'],
 false, 6);

-- TAXES 11: Multi-State Tax Nexus
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'compliance', 'Multi-State Tax Nexus for SaaS Companies',
 'Economic nexus rules for IN/OH/IL/MI, Wayfair implications for SaaS, apportionment, P.L. 86-272, and state registration requirements.',
 E'## Multi-State Tax Nexus for SaaS Companies\n\nAs Ascent XR sells to school districts across state lines, understanding multi-state tax obligations is critical. A single sale to an Ohio school district could trigger Ohio filing requirements.\n\n### Economic Nexus Post-Wayfair\n\nThe 2018 Supreme Court decision in **South Dakota v. Wayfair** established that states can require businesses to collect sales tax based on **economic presence** alone, without any physical presence in the state. Most states have adopted economic nexus thresholds:\n\n**Surrounding State Thresholds (Sales Tax)**:\n\n| State | Revenue Threshold | Transaction Threshold | Rate |\n|-------|-------------------|----------------------|------|\n| Indiana | $100,000 | 200 transactions | 7.0% |\n| Ohio | $100,000 | 200 transactions | 5.75% (+ local) |\n| Illinois | $100,000 | 200 transactions | 6.25% (+ local) |\n| Michigan | $100,000 | 200 transactions | 6.0% |\n| Kentucky | $100,000 | 200 transactions | 6.0% |\n\nYou must collect and remit sales tax in a state once you exceed **either** the revenue OR transaction threshold in the current or prior calendar year.\n\n### Physical vs. Economic Presence\n\n**Physical nexus** is created by:\n- Having employees working in the state (even remotely)\n- Maintaining an office, warehouse, or inventory in the state\n- Attending trade shows or conferences (some states, for extended presence)\n- Visiting client sites for delivery, training, or sales meetings (varies by state)\n\n**Economic nexus** is created by:\n- Exceeding the state''s revenue threshold from sales into the state\n- Exceeding the transaction count threshold\n- Having a significant number of customers in the state\n\nFor Ascent XR, visiting an Ohio school district for a demo or training session could create physical nexus in Ohio regardless of revenue levels.\n\n### Factor-Based Apportionment\n\nFor **income tax** purposes (not sales tax), multi-state businesses apportion income among states using factors:\n\n- Most states now use **single-factor apportionment** based on sales/revenue\n- Some states still use three-factor (property, payroll, sales) or modified formulas\n- **Indiana**: Uses single-factor apportionment (sales factor only) for corporate income tax\n- **Ohio**: Commercial Activity Tax (CAT) at 0.26% on gross receipts over $1 million -- a separate gross receipts tax\n- **Illinois**: Single-factor sales apportionment for corporate income tax\n- **Michigan**: Single-factor sales apportionment; 6% Corporate Income Tax\n\n### P.L. 86-272 Protection\n\n**Public Law 86-272** provides limited protection from state income tax for businesses whose only activity in a state is soliciting orders for tangible personal property:\n\n- **Does NOT protect SaaS companies**: P.L. 86-272 only applies to tangible personal property. SaaS and services are explicitly excluded.\n- **Does NOT protect service providers**: If you deliver professional services (training, consulting) in another state, 86-272 offers no protection\n- **Practical impact for Ascent XR**: Cannot rely on 86-272 protection because SaaS subscriptions are not tangible personal property. Any nexus-creating activity in another state (economic or physical) could trigger income tax filing requirements.\n- Many states (including California and New York) have updated their guidance to explicitly exclude digital goods and SaaS from 86-272 protection\n\n### State-by-State Registration Requirements\n\nWhen you establish nexus in a new state:\n\n1. **Register for sales tax** collection (if the state taxes SaaS)\n2. **Register for income/franchise tax** filing\n3. **Register as a foreign LLC** if you have physical presence (employees, office)\n4. **File annual/periodic returns** as required\n\nKey SaaS taxability by surrounding state:\n\n| State | SaaS Taxable? | Notes |\n|-------|--------------|-------|\n| Indiana | **Yes** | 7% sales tax |\n| Ohio | **Generally No** | But subject to CAT on gross receipts |\n| Illinois | **Yes** | As electronic delivery of software |\n| Michigan | **No** | SaaS not considered tangible personal property |\n| Kentucky | **Yes** | Taxable as digital property |\n\n### Voluntary Disclosure Programs\n\nIf you discover you had nexus in a state but were not filing:\n\n- Most states offer **Voluntary Disclosure Agreements (VDAs)** through the Multistate Tax Commission or directly with the state\n- Typical benefits: Look-back period limited to 3-4 years, penalties waived, interest negotiable\n- Must not have been previously contacted by the state about the liability\n- **Recommendation**: Conduct a nexus study once revenue exceeds $50,000 from any single state to proactively identify filing obligations\n\n### Sales Tax Nexus Thresholds Summary\n\nThe general threshold across most states is **$100,000 in revenue OR 200 transactions** within the state. However, several states have different thresholds:\n\n- California: $500,000 (revenue only, no transaction threshold)\n- New York: $500,000 AND 100 transactions (both must be met)\n- Texas: $500,000 (revenue only)\n- Florida: $100,000 (revenue only, no transaction count)\n\nMonitor your state-by-state revenue quarterly using your CRM or accounting system to identify approaching thresholds.',
 ARRAY['multi-state', 'nexus', 'Wayfair', 'sales-tax', 'apportionment', 'PL-86-272', 'economic-nexus', 'SaaS-taxability'],
 false, 7);

-- TAXES 12: Tax Implications of LLC-to-Corp Conversion
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('taxes', 'entity-structure', 'Tax Implications of LLC-to-Corporation Conversion',
 'Section 351 requirements, timing considerations, Indiana conversion steps, S-Corp election deadlines, and impacts on contracts and accounting.',
 E'## Tax Implications of LLC-to-Corporation Conversion\n\nMany startups begin as LLCs for simplicity and later convert to a corporation for investment, equity compensation, or tax purposes. Understanding the tax implications ensures a smooth, tax-efficient transition.\n\n### Section 351 Tax-Free Incorporation\n\nThe conversion of an LLC to a corporation can be structured as a **tax-free transaction** under Section 351 of the Internal Revenue Code if:\n\n1. **Control Test**: The person(s) transferring assets to the corporation must own at least **80% of the corporation''s stock** immediately after the transfer. For a single-member LLC converting to a single-shareholder corporation, this is automatically satisfied.\n2. **Property Transfer**: The LLC''s assets (and liabilities) are transferred to the corporation in exchange for stock. The LLC members receive stock equal to their membership interests.\n3. **No Boot**: If any member receives cash or other property (\"boot\") in addition to stock, the boot is taxable. Keep the conversion as stock-only.\n\n**Tax basis**: In a 351 transaction, the corporation takes a **carryover basis** in the assets (same basis the LLC had), and the shareholders take a **substituted basis** in the stock (same as their LLC interest basis). No gain or loss is recognized.\n\n**Key risk**: If the LLC has liabilities exceeding the aggregate basis of assets transferred, the excess is treated as gain to the transferor under Section 357(c). This is rare but must be checked.\n\n### Timing Considerations\n\n**Calendar Year vs. Fiscal Year**:\n- Most LLCs and S-Corps use a **calendar year** (January 1 - December 31)\n- The conversion creates a short tax year for the LLC (January 1 to conversion date) and a short tax year for the corporation (conversion date to December 31)\n- **Best timing**: Convert on **January 1** to avoid short-year returns and simplify compliance\n- If converting mid-year, file a final LLC return for the short period and a short-year corporate return\n\n**Tax planning**: If converting from LLC to S-Corp, consider timing the conversion for early in the year when accumulated earnings are low, minimizing the accumulated adjustments account (AAA) complexity.\n\n### Indiana State Conversion Steps\n\n1. **File Articles of Conversion** with the Indiana Secretary of State through **INBiz.in.gov**\n   - Filing fee: **$95** (online)\n   - Specifies the converting entity (LLC) and the resulting entity (corporation)\n   - Include Articles of Incorporation for the new corporation\n\n2. **Update BT-1 registration** with the Indiana DOR to reflect the new entity type\n\n3. **Notify county assessor** if you have business personal property on file\n\n4. **Update business licenses and permits** with any local government agencies\n\n5. Indiana recognizes statutory conversions under IC 23-0.6, which means the corporation is a **continuation** of the LLC -- it retains the same EIN, contracts, and legal standing unless changed.\n\n### EIN Changes\n\n- **Statutory conversion** (LLC converts directly to corporation under state law): The IRS position is that a **new EIN is required** when the entity type changes for tax purposes (e.g., from disregarded entity/partnership to corporation)\n- Apply for the new EIN on IRS.gov immediately upon conversion\n- Update the new EIN with: banks, customers, vendors, payroll providers, state tax agencies, insurance companies\n- **Exception**: If the LLC was already taxed as a corporation (by previous election), no new EIN is needed\n\n### Accounting Method Changes\n\n- An LLC taxed as a sole proprietorship or partnership may use the **cash method** of accounting\n- A C-Corporation with average annual gross receipts exceeding **$29 million** (2024 threshold) must use the **accrual method**\n- S-Corporations can generally use the cash method regardless of revenue\n- If a method change is required, file **Form 3115** (Application for Change in Accounting Method) with the IRS\n- Timing: File Form 3115 during the first tax year of the new entity\n\n### S-Corp Election Deadline\n\nIf converting to an S-Corporation (most common for small businesses):\n\n- File **Form 2553** (Election by a Small Business Corporation)\n- **Deadline**: Within **75 days** of the corporation''s formation date (the conversion effective date)\n- Alternatively, file by **March 15** for the election to be effective for the current calendar year\n- If the deadline is missed, the IRS may grant **late election relief** if you can demonstrate reasonable cause (Revenue Procedure 2013-30)\n- All shareholders must consent to the S-Corp election by signing Form 2553\n- Indiana automatically follows the federal S-Corp election -- no separate state election is required\n\n### Impact on Existing Contracts\n\nStatutory conversion preserves contract continuity:\n\n- Under Indiana''s entity conversion statute, the resulting entity (corporation) is deemed the **same entity** as the converting entity (LLC)\n- All contracts, agreements, leases, and obligations transfer automatically\n- However, **review all contracts** for change-of-control or assignment clauses that may be triggered\n- Notify key customers and vendors of the entity name change\n- Update your W-9 information with all customers (new entity name, possibly new EIN)\n- Bank accounts may need to be re-titled or new accounts opened\n\n### Tax Return Filing in the Conversion Year\n\nAssuming a mid-year conversion (e.g., July 1):\n\n| Period | Return | Entity |\n|--------|--------|--------|\n| Jan 1 - Jun 30 | Final Form 1065 or Schedule C (short year) | LLC |\n| Jul 1 - Dec 31 | Form 1120-S (short year, if S-Corp elected) | Corporation |\n| Full year | Indiana IT-65 (short) + IT-20S (short) | Both |\n| Full year | Individual Form IT-40 with both K-1s | Owner |\n\n**Best practice**: Work with a CPA experienced in entity conversions to ensure all returns are filed correctly and the transition is properly documented. Budget $2,000-$4,000 for professional fees related to the conversion.',
 ARRAY['LLC-to-Corp', 'Section-351', 'conversion', 'S-Corp-election', 'Form-2553', 'Indiana', 'EIN', 'Articles-of-Conversion'],
 false, 7);


