-- CUSTOMER SUCCESS 1: K-12 EdTech Customer Success Fundamentals
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('customer_success', 'fundamentals', 'K-12 EdTech Customer Success Fundamentals',
 'Foundational customer success principles for the K-12 education market including buyer journey, critical success factors, and school calendar awareness.',
 E'## K-12 EdTech Customer Success Fundamentals\n\nCustomer success in K-12 education is fundamentally different from B2B SaaS. The buyer is rarely the user, adoption depends on teacher buy-in, and the entire calendar revolves around the school year.\n\n### The K-12 Buyer Journey\n\nUnderstanding the journey from purchase to renewal is critical:\n\n1. **Purchase Decision** (made by administrators): Superintendent, CTO, or curriculum director signs the contract. They care about ROI, compliance, and board-reportable outcomes.\n2. **Implementation** (managed by IT and admin): Technology team deploys devices, configures accounts, and ensures network compatibility. They care about ease of setup and support responsiveness.\n3. **Adoption** (driven by teachers): Classroom teachers are the actual users. They care about ease of use, lesson plan integration, and student engagement. **If teachers don''t adopt, the product fails regardless of admin enthusiasm.**\n4. **Value Realization** (measured by all): Student outcomes, usage data, and engagement metrics determine whether the purchase was justified.\n5. **Renewal Decision** (back to administrators): Based on adoption data, teacher feedback, and measurable outcomes. Renewal conversations start 90 days before contract expiration.\n\n### Critical Success Factors\n\n- **Teacher Champion**: Identify and cultivate at least one passionate teacher advocate per building. This person drives peer adoption and provides authentic testimonials.\n- **Quick Win**: Deliver a visible success within the first 30 days. One compelling classroom experience that teachers talk about in the lounge is worth more than any marketing material.\n- **Admin Visibility**: Ensure administrators receive regular usage reports and outcome data. They need ammunition for board meetings and budget justifications.\n- **Low Friction**: Every barrier to teacher use -- login complexity, device setup time, content search difficulty -- directly reduces adoption. Eliminate friction relentlessly.\n\n### School Calendar Awareness\n\n| Period | CS Focus | Key Activities |\n|--------|----------|----------------|\n| **Aug-Sep** | Onboarding | New implementations, teacher training, back-to-school setup |\n| **Oct-Nov** | Adoption | Usage monitoring, teacher support, first engagement reports |\n| **Dec** | Light touch | Holiday break approaching; avoid scheduling training |\n| **Jan-Feb** | Deepening | Advanced training, expand usage to new classrooms, mid-year check-in |\n| **Mar-Apr** | Value proof | Compile outcome data, prepare renewal materials, QBR with admin |\n| **May-Jun** | Renewal | Renewal conversations, expansion proposals, year-end reporting |\n| **Jun-Aug** | Planning | Summer PD sessions, next-year planning, implementation prep |\n\n**Critical rule**: Never schedule teacher training during state testing windows (typically March-May). Teachers are stressed and unavailable.',
 ARRAY['customer-success', 'K-12', 'buyer-journey', 'teacher-adoption', 'school-calendar', 'fundamentals'],
 true, 10);

-- CUSTOMER SUCCESS 2: Onboarding Playbook: 60-Day Framework
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('customer_success', 'onboarding', 'Onboarding Playbook: 60-Day Framework',
 'Week-by-week onboarding plan for new K-12 district implementations with checklists, milestones, and escalation triggers.',
 E'## Onboarding Playbook: 60-Day Framework\n\nThe first 60 days after contract signing determine long-term success. This playbook provides a structured, repeatable process for onboarding new school district customers.\n\n### Week 1: Kickoff & Technical Setup\n\n**Checklist**:\n- [ ] Send welcome email with named CSM introduction within 24 hours of contract signing\n- [ ] Schedule kickoff call with district champion, IT contact, and building principals\n- [ ] Conduct kickoff call: review goals, timeline, success metrics, and communication preferences\n- [ ] Provide IT setup documentation (network requirements, device configuration, SSO setup)\n- [ ] Create customer record in CS platform with all contact information\n- [ ] Establish shared communication channel (email thread or Teams/Slack)\n\n### Week 2: Technical Deployment\n\n**Checklist**:\n- [ ] IT team completes network configuration and device enrollment\n- [ ] Verify platform access for all administrator accounts\n- [ ] Test content delivery on school network (bandwidth, firewall, proxy)\n- [ ] Configure SSO integration with district identity provider (Google, Clever, ClassLink)\n- [ ] Resolve any technical blockers within 48 hours\n- [ ] Confirm deployment complete with IT contact sign-off\n\n### Weeks 3-4: Teacher Training\n\n**Checklist**:\n- [ ] Schedule training sessions (in-person preferred, virtual available)\n- [ ] Deliver Session 1: Platform basics, device handling, content navigation (90 minutes)\n- [ ] Deliver Session 2: Lesson integration, assessment tools, student management (90 minutes)\n- [ ] Provide quick-reference guides and video tutorials\n- [ ] Identify 1-2 teacher champions per building for peer support\n- [ ] Set up teacher feedback channel for ongoing questions\n- [ ] Confirm at least 80% of target teachers attended training\n\n### Weeks 5-6: Guided First Use\n\n**Checklist**:\n- [ ] CSM available for first classroom session (in-person or virtual shadow)\n- [ ] Monitor daily usage metrics -- flag any building with zero usage\n- [ ] Proactive outreach to teachers who have not logged in\n- [ ] Address any content or technical issues reported\n- [ ] Share early usage data with district champion\n- [ ] Celebrate first wins (student reactions, teacher feedback) in shared channel\n\n### Weeks 7-8: Adoption Review\n\n**Checklist**:\n- [ ] Compile 60-day onboarding report: usage metrics, teacher feedback, technical issues resolved\n- [ ] Schedule 60-day review meeting with district champion and admin stakeholders\n- [ ] Present adoption data and initial engagement metrics\n- [ ] Identify barriers to broader adoption and create action plan\n- [ ] Transition from onboarding cadence to ongoing success cadence\n- [ ] Document lessons learned for process improvement\n\n### Escalation Triggers\n\n- **Red**: Zero usage from any building after Week 4 -- escalate to district champion and CSM manager\n- **Yellow**: Less than 50% of trained teachers active by Week 6 -- proactive outreach and additional training\n- **Green**: 70%+ teacher adoption by Week 8 -- celebrate and plan expansion',
 ARRAY['onboarding', 'implementation', '60-day', 'playbook', 'checklist', 'teacher-training', 'deployment'],
 false, 9);

-- CUSTOMER SUCCESS 3: Health Scoring Methodology
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('customer_success', 'methodology', 'Health Scoring Methodology',
 'Weighted customer health scoring system with Usage (25%), Engagement (30%), Support (20%), and Adoption (25%) dimensions including signal thresholds.',
 E'## Health Scoring Methodology\n\nA robust health scoring system provides early warning of at-risk accounts and highlights expansion opportunities. This methodology is designed specifically for K-12 EdTech customers.\n\n### Scoring Dimensions & Weights\n\n| Dimension | Weight | What It Measures |\n|-----------|--------|------------------|\n| **Usage** | 25% | Platform activity volume and consistency |\n| **Engagement** | 30% | Stakeholder relationship depth and responsiveness |\n| **Support** | 20% | Support ticket patterns and satisfaction |\n| **Adoption** | 25% | Breadth and depth of product usage across the district |\n\n### Usage Score (25% weight)\n\nMeasures how actively the platform is being used:\n\n| Signal | Green (8-10) | Yellow (4-7) | Red (0-3) |\n|--------|-------------|-------------|----------|\n| Monthly active teachers | >70% of licensed | 40-70% of licensed | <40% of licensed |\n| Sessions per teacher/month | 8+ sessions | 3-7 sessions | <3 sessions |\n| Content modules accessed | 5+ unique modules | 2-4 modules | 0-1 modules |\n| Usage trend (30-day) | Increasing or stable | Slight decline (<15%) | Declining >15% |\n\n### Engagement Score (30% weight)\n\nMeasures the quality of the customer relationship:\n\n| Signal | Green (8-10) | Yellow (4-7) | Red (0-3) |\n|--------|-------------|-------------|----------|\n| QBR attendance | Admin + teachers attend | Admin attends, no teachers | QBR declined or no-show |\n| Email response time | <48 hours | 2-5 days | >5 days or no response |\n| Executive sponsor access | Regular contact with superintendent/CTO | Contact through intermediaries | No executive access |\n| Reference willingness | Actively refers | Willing if asked | Declines or avoids |\n| Feature feedback | Proactively shares ideas | Responds to surveys | No feedback engagement |\n\n### Support Score (20% weight)\n\nMeasures support health -- lower ticket volume with high satisfaction is ideal:\n\n| Signal | Green (8-10) | Yellow (4-7) | Red (0-3) |\n|--------|-------------|-------------|----------|\n| Open ticket count | 0-1 open tickets | 2-3 open tickets | 4+ open or any P1 unresolved |\n| Ticket sentiment | Positive/neutral | Mixed | Negative or escalated |\n| Resolution satisfaction | CSAT 4-5 stars | CSAT 3 stars | CSAT 1-2 stars |\n| Time to resolution | Within SLA | SLA borderline | SLA breached |\n\n### Adoption Score (25% weight)\n\nMeasures how deeply embedded the product is in the district:\n\n| Signal | Green (8-10) | Yellow (4-7) | Red (0-3) |\n|--------|-------------|-------------|----------|\n| Buildings using platform | >75% of district buildings | 40-75% of buildings | <40% of buildings |\n| Grade levels covered | 3+ grade levels | 2 grade levels | 1 grade level only |\n| Subject areas | Cross-curricular (3+ subjects) | 2 subjects | Single subject |\n| Integration depth | SSO + LMS integrated | SSO only | Standalone login |\n\n### Overall Health Calculation\n\n**Health Score = (Usage x 0.25) + (Engagement x 0.30) + (Support x 0.20) + (Adoption x 0.25)**\n\n- **Healthy (8-10)**: Low churn risk, expansion candidate. Review quarterly.\n- **Neutral (5-7)**: Monitor monthly. Identify specific areas to improve.\n- **At Risk (0-4)**: Immediate intervention. CSM creates save plan within 48 hours.',
 ARRAY['health-score', 'customer-health', 'methodology', 'usage-metrics', 'engagement', 'adoption', 'churn-risk'],
 false, 9);

-- CUSTOMER SUCCESS 4: Retention & Expansion Playbook
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('customer_success', 'retention', 'Retention & Expansion Playbook',
 'Structured renewal process with 90-60-30 day sequence, expansion signal identification, and save plays for at-risk accounts.',
 E'## Retention & Expansion Playbook\n\nRetaining existing customers is 5-7x more cost-effective than acquiring new ones. In K-12, where referrals drive the majority of new business, every lost customer is also a lost reference.\n\n### 90-60-30 Renewal Sequence\n\n**Day 90 Before Expiration: Renewal Kickoff**\n- Review account health score and usage trends\n- Schedule renewal planning call with district champion\n- Prepare renewal package with usage report, outcomes summary, and pricing options\n- Identify expansion opportunities (additional buildings, grade levels, content areas)\n- If health score is red, initiate save play immediately (see below)\n\n**Day 60 Before Expiration: Proposal Delivery**\n- Present renewal proposal with clear value summary\n- Include year-over-year comparison data (usage growth, student impact)\n- Offer early renewal incentive (5% discount for signing 60+ days early)\n- Address any open concerns or unresolved issues\n- Confirm the decision maker and approval process for renewal\n- Flag to leadership if renewal is uncertain\n\n**Day 30 Before Expiration: Close & Process**\n- Follow up on proposal status\n- Assist with PO creation and budget code allocation\n- Ensure all paperwork is in the district''s procurement pipeline\n- For at-risk renewals, offer bridge pricing or month-to-month extension while negotiating\n- Confirm renewal signed and process implementation of any changes\n\n### Expansion Signals\n\nWatch for these indicators that a district is ready to expand:\n\n- **Usage ceiling hit**: Teachers requesting access for additional classrooms or grade levels\n- **Cross-building interest**: Principals from non-licensed buildings asking about the platform\n- **Content requests**: Teachers asking for modules in subjects not currently covered\n- **Conference mentions**: District staff mentioning Ascent XR at education conferences\n- **New funding**: District receives new grant or budget allocation for technology\n- **Leadership praise**: Superintendent or board members citing XR program in public meetings\n\n### Expansion Conversation Framework\n\nWhen expansion signals appear:\n1. Acknowledge the success: \"Your teachers have done incredible work with the platform\"\n2. Quantify the impact: \"Lincoln Elementary saw 42% more engagement in science modules\"\n3. Suggest natural next step: \"Imagine bringing that same experience to your 4th and 5th grade classrooms\"\n4. Offer expansion pricing: Volume discounts for additional building licenses\n5. Propose a mini-pilot: Let the new building try it for 2 weeks before committing\n\n### Save Plays for At-Risk Accounts\n\n**Low Usage Save**:\n- Diagnose root cause (technical issues? teacher turnover? no champion?)\n- Offer complimentary re-training session for new or struggling teachers\n- Assign a dedicated CSM for weekly check-ins for 30 days\n- Create a custom usage acceleration plan with the district champion\n\n**Executive Sponsor Loss Save**:\n- Immediately identify the new decision maker\n- Request introduction from existing contacts\n- Prepare a fresh value presentation for the new stakeholder\n- Offer a \"reset\" meeting to align on goals and expectations\n\n**Budget Concern Save**:\n- Present ROI analysis with district-specific data\n- Offer flexible payment terms (quarterly vs. annual)\n- Propose a reduced scope (fewer buildings) rather than full cancellation\n- Connect to funding sources (Title IV-A, state technology grants)',
 ARRAY['retention', 'renewal', 'expansion', 'save-plays', 'churn-prevention', '90-60-30', 'upsell'],
 false, 8);

-- CUSTOMER SUCCESS 5: NPS and CSAT Measurement Strategy
INSERT INTO knowledge_base_articles (business_area, category, title, summary, content, tags, is_pinned, priority) VALUES
('customer_success', 'measurement', 'NPS and CSAT Measurement Strategy',
 'Survey methodology for NPS and CSAT measurement including timing, targets, response frameworks, and action plans for each score range.',
 E'## NPS and CSAT Measurement Strategy\n\nMeasuring customer satisfaction and loyalty provides actionable data for improving the product, the customer experience, and ultimately retention rates.\n\n### Net Promoter Score (NPS)\n\n**The Question**: \"On a scale of 0-10, how likely are you to recommend Ascent XR to a colleague at another school district?\"\n\n**Scoring**:\n- **Promoters (9-10)**: Loyal enthusiasts who will refer and advocate\n- **Passives (7-8)**: Satisfied but not enthusiastic; vulnerable to competitors\n- **Detractors (0-6)**: Unhappy customers who can damage your reputation\n- **NPS = % Promoters - % Detractors** (range: -100 to +100)\n\n**Survey Timing**:\n- Send NPS surveys **twice per year**: November (after fall adoption) and April (before renewal season)\n- Never survey during the first 60 days of implementation (too early to judge)\n- Never survey during state testing windows (March-May in most states)\n- Allow 2 weeks for responses before closing the survey\n\n**Targets**:\n- **Year 1 target**: NPS of +30 (good for EdTech)\n- **Year 2 target**: NPS of +45 (excellent)\n- **World-class EdTech**: NPS of +60 or higher\n- Industry average for EdTech SaaS: +20 to +35\n\n### Customer Satisfaction Score (CSAT)\n\n**The Question**: \"How satisfied are you with [specific interaction]?\" (1-5 star scale)\n\n**When to Measure CSAT**:\n- After every support ticket resolution (automated email)\n- After onboarding completion (end of 60-day survey)\n- After training sessions (immediate post-session)\n- After QBR meetings (follow-up email within 24 hours)\n\n**Targets**:\n- Support CSAT: 4.5+ stars (90%+ satisfaction)\n- Onboarding CSAT: 4.3+ stars\n- Training CSAT: 4.5+ stars\n- Overall CSAT: 4.2+ stars\n\n### Action Framework by Score\n\n**Promoters (NPS 9-10) / CSAT 5 stars**:\n- Thank them personally within 48 hours\n- Ask for a testimonial or case study participation\n- Invite to reference call list for prospective customers\n- Nominate for customer advisory board\n- Send to G2/Capterra for public review\n\n**Passives (NPS 7-8) / CSAT 3-4 stars**:\n- Follow up with a brief phone call to understand what would make it a 9 or 10\n- Identify specific improvement areas and create action plan\n- Schedule a check-in in 30 days to report on improvements made\n- These customers are the biggest opportunity -- small improvements convert them to promoters\n\n**Detractors (NPS 0-6) / CSAT 1-2 stars**:\n- CSM calls within 24 hours (not email -- phone call)\n- Listen first. Do not get defensive. Document every concern.\n- Create a written recovery plan with specific actions and timeline\n- Escalate to CS leadership if the issue is systemic\n- Follow up weekly until the issue is resolved\n- Re-survey in 60 days to measure improvement\n\n### Reporting Cadence\n\n- **Weekly**: Review all new detractor responses and ensure follow-up is underway\n- **Monthly**: CSAT trends by category (support, training, onboarding)\n- **Quarterly**: NPS trend analysis, segment by district size, region, and contract vintage\n- **Annually**: Year-over-year NPS comparison, correlation with retention rates',
 ARRAY['NPS', 'CSAT', 'customer-satisfaction', 'surveys', 'measurement', 'promoters', 'detractors', 'action-framework'],
 false, 7);


